deck_description:
the first cards you want to stat off with either your going second or first is either 1 of the 2 live twin monsters or cynet mining to add one to your hand. then summon one and activate its effect to special out of the deck the other live twin monster. Then at this point you will need to make a decision based on if you went first or second. if you went first link into kiskil then summon from the grave the other live twin to then link into lilla to then activate her effect summoning back kiskil (the link monster) to then draw a card. if you went second do what i just said but with the other twins. But the end effect will be to destroy a card on the field. then i would either link those two into unchained abomination and see if you have a unchained trap in hand to set it then end then activate abomination to pop it or to pop an opponents card. All the trap cards have primary effects that do different things but they all have similar secondary effects. these effects allows you to summon an unchained monster from the hand, deck or grave if the trap gets destroyed by card effect. This also counts for your own cards destroying them. This is the main strategies for the unchained monsters. Ive added to the deck some XYZ coverage with Numbers 97, 107 and 38 all rank 8. these can be summoned by the two level 8 monsters in the deck which are:

Abominable Unchained Soul

and

Unchained Soul of Disaster.

If you are going to XYZ summon then i would go into number 97 as he can summon (by its effect) one of the other rank 8 monsters by attaching the other to it as an XYZ material. In this deck you need to play lots of interruptions such as ash to stop your effects being negated and to stop your opponent making unstoppable boards with lots of negates. That's all you really need to know but that's not the only combos you can do with it but I feel like you need to find some out on your own. One more thing I've play tested this deck out many times on nexus and went 5:0 with this deck on there so I know its competitive and is a very strong rouge deck.
Ran out of ideas for the extra and side. F

deck_excerpt: The deck heavily focuses on Rank 4 XYZs and particularly getting out Time Thief Redoer and stuffing him with materials.
deck_description:
Time Thief archetype is a pretty fun archetype that can be somewhat of a control deck. Note for my build, some of the cards aren't officially out yet. Some of the biggest issues with the deck are with consistency, not many monster effect negates, board control, or pump out big beaters to get over stuff. When playing the deck you want to play more defensive and more control based. I made the deck as a mix going 1st and going 2nd. As in having options while going 1st or 2nd. So in my build, I decided to tech 2 cards (Evenly Match and XYZ Import). And my extra deck has few board control options like Evilswarm Exciton Knight and Castle. But I will explain more about this deck while going on. Monsters (19): 3x Ash Blossom - Standard Hand Trap. You need some sort of hand trap nowadays, too many can be cloggy so currently, Ash Blossom is one of the safest ones to main. 3x Time Thief Regulator - I recommend trying to bait out Ash Blossom before summoning this guy 1st. This guy has 2 jobs for you, when he is normal to summon, you can tribute him while you have no monster to special summon 2 Time Thief monsters from your deck. I recommend for your targets to be Winder and Adjuster. Both of their effects will kick up once you summon them. It also has a GY effect where if your XYZ monster was destroyed by battle you can special summon it from the grave but it is banished when it leaves the field. 3X Time Thief Winder - He is practically the Stratos for this deck, he can search out Time Thief cards and I would recommend using his effect to search out Time Thief Retrograde or Flyback. You can also special summon him from your hand by detecting materials from a Time Thief XYZ. 2x Time Thief Chronocorder - I would recommend running 1 or 2 copies. It has a graveyard effect that can special summon itself when your XYZ (partially Redoer) leaves the field with its own effect. 3 x Time Thief Adjuster - She can easily special summon herself if you normal or special summon a Time Thief monster and has a "Foolish Burial" effect that can dump any Time Thief card in the grave. I would recommend using her effect to dump Chronocorder or Bezel Ship in the grave but heavily recommend using it to dump Time Thief Startup/Time Thief Flyback in the grave using her effect. Since these cards have graveyard effects. 1x Time Thief Bezel Ship - I would recommend running 1 or 2 of this guy. It can special summon itself from the grave by removing XYZ material from a Time Thief XYZ but it banishes itself after it leaves the field. For this deck, I am running a "Performage" Engine. 1x Performage Damage Juggler - I recommend foolish burial him and either get Trick Clown or Hat Tricker to hand but if you draw into him you can still normal summon him or use him as a hand trap to not take damage. 1x Performage Trick Clown - one the best stall, Foolish Burial target and XYZ material card, his effect is "If this card is sent to the GY: you can target 1 "Performage" monster in your GY: Special Summon it, but its ATK/DEF become 0, then you take 1000 damage 1000 damage. You can only use this effect of "Performage Trick Clown" once per turn. I love this guy in my Lightsworns build but he is also handy here especially since you are trying to get into rank 4 XYZs. You can detach him as XYZ material and his effects still go off. 2x Performage Hat Tricker - One of the good Performage monsters even when you go 2nd. It special summon itself if there are more than 2 monsters on the field, so if you go 2nd, you can just special summon him easily and not lose your normal summon that turn. Spells (12): 1x Instant Fusion - It is an extender to help get out your XYZ or even link plays. I am using this summon Darkfire Dragon to kick off XYZ plays. 1x Foolish Burial - you have a few Foolish Burial targets in this deck such as Trick Clown, Damage Juggler, Regulator, Chronocorder, and Bezel. 1x Monster Reborn and 1x Called by the Grave - They are good generic staples to have in hand. 2x Time Thief Startup - I mostly use it for its GY effect but it also works as a double summon to help to get "Time Thief" monsters on board for XYZ plays. Its GY is written as "During your Main Phase: You can banish this card from your GY, then target 1 "Time Thief" XYZ Monster you control: attach 3 "Time Thief" cards of different types (1 Monster, 1 Spell, and 1 Trap) from your GY to that monster as Material". You can search this card using Winder or dump it in grave using Adjuster 1x Time Thief Hack - you don't have to run this card, but for my build, it is helpful to get over stuff or finish for the game. It also gives a protection effect for your "Time Thief" monsters during the turn they are summoned, they can't be destroyed by your opponent's card effects. This helps especially if you are going 2nd. You can even attack directly using its effect if you already have your opponent's material as XYZ material and give a 300 attack boost per material that is attached. I would recommend running 1 and it is searchable. 2x XYZ Import - This is a good going 1st card, especially if you know your opponent has to start their play with a monster that has less than your XYZ monster, most of the time you are going to start out with Redoer either way so anything less than 2400 ATK that your opponent controls will turn into an XYZ material. If you do it right, you can pretty much stop anything your opponent do for the turn. 2x Pot of Disparity - I generally prefer this card over Desires (especially since most decks do run Ash) or Extravagance. Because you get to control what you are banishing, from your extra deck and try to dig out what card you need especially if you going for games 2/3 where you are trying to search out your key side deck card. Its Duality effect doesn't restrict special summoning which is important on turn 1. If you don't want to banish anything or want more draw power, I strongly suggest Allure of Darkness 12 Dark Monsters, over something like Desires. I generally am against running Desires because Ash exists and also if you run decks that have a lot of darks or need cards in the grave. 1x Pot of Avarice - You are going to need to recycle all your monsters, XYZs or not. It can be cloggy running multiply so running 1 is good enough. Traps (11) 3x Time Thief Retrograde - This card is your Spell and Trap shield and turns your opponent spell/trap into XYZ material. 3x Time Thief Flyback - You can stuff your opponent's GY cards if it is set as material if it is in the grave or stuff cards from your deck into Time Thief XYZ Monsters. 2x The Phantom Knights of Shade Brigandine - It is a trap monster that can be used for rank 4 XYZ, if you don't have traps in your grave on your 1st turn, you can activate him right away. 3x Evenly Matched - One of the best board wipes in the game and with Redoer's effect, you can easily use him on your turn if you have nothing field. And it is one of the best cards especially going 2nd. This card single handly will make Hero's player rage quit after they set up their board because of their lower monster count, take care of annoying unbreakable boards, etc. Extra deck (15) 1x Darkflare Dragon - you only have him for Instant Fusion target or banish for Pot of Disparity if you want. You just it for that necessarily filler. 2x Time Thief Redoer - He is basically the boss monster for this deck and he is also a generic rank 4 that you can splash around in other decks. His effects read as "Once per turn, during the Standby Phase: You can attach the top card of your opponent's Deck to this card as material. (Quick Effect): You can detach up to 3 different types of materials from this card, then apply the following effect(s) depending on what was detached.
● Monster: Banish this card until the End Phase. ● Spell: Draw 1 card. ● Trap: Place 1 face-up card your opponent controls on the top of the Deck. You can only use this effect of "Time Thief Redoer" once per turn."
The goal for this deck is to stuff cards into him either from your opponent's side or yours and using his effects to draw cards, banish itself to not get destroyed, or place a face-up back on top of the deck.
2x - Time Thief Perpetual - She has 2 good effects, during each standby phase she can stuff cards into Redoer, Doublebarrel, or another copy of herself. You can use her effect to special summon Time Thief monsters from the grave as well.
1x - Time Thief Doublebarrel - I would also recommend a 2nd copy but 1 is good enough because you need stuff cards in him instead of something natural like Redoer can do. But his effects are worth it. Because he can turn into mind control or negate the effect a monster your opponent controls on the field. His effects read as:
"When your opponent activates a card or effect (Quick Effect): You can detach up to 3 different types of materials from this card, then apply the following effect(s) depending on what was detached. ● Monster: This card gains 400 ATK. ● Spell: Take control of 1 face-up monster your opponent controls until the End Phase, but it cannot declare an attack or activate its effects this turn. ● Trap: Negate the effects of 1 Effect Monster on the field until the end of this turn. You can only use this effect of "Time Thief Doublebarrel" once per turn."
2x Castel - a decent rank 4 to go into and helps to get certain cards on the field
1x Evilswarm Exciton Knight - He is one of the best rank 4 board wipes to get out
1x Evilswarm Nightmare - Since you run a lot of dark attribute monsters, you can easily get this guy out to book your opponent monster, if they are running stuff like "Sky Strikers or heavy on the Link" he is useless but most decks, he is still good putting some board controls.
1x Abyss Dweller - Graveyard is like a 2nd hand, you can shut down your Opponent's second hand.
1x I:P Masquerena, Pheonix, Unicorn - Generic links that are good go-to.
1x Infinitrack Fortress Megaclops - "Unaffected by other monsters' effects, except those of Xyz Monsters. Cannot be destroyed by battle, except with an Xyz Monster. You can target 1 Xyz Monster in your GY and 1 card your opponent controls; Special Summon that monster from your GY, and if you do, attach that opponent's card to it as material, also for the rest of this turn, any damage your opponent takes is halved. You can only use this effect of "Infinitrack Fortress Megaclops" once per turn." This card is great for XYZ heavy decks and also a 4k beater to get over your opponent's monsters.
Side Deck (15)
3x Nibiru - for those heavy Special Summon and spam decks.
3x Gamma + 1x Driver - a good hand trap option especially if you are going 2nd.
1x Dimensional Fissure - You can run Dimensional Fissure as a possible floodgate. Because it doesn't banish XYZ materials. but put it when you are done setting up.
3x Cosmic Cyclone - A lot of meta decks have Spell and Traps with GY effects so it is better to get them banished.
3x Dark Ruler No More - Best go 2nd card after Evenly Matched, especially if you know they are running annoy stuff like Dragoon.
1x Red Reboot - If you go 2nd or you know your opponent runs a lot of annoying traps, this card takes care of them. Especially for the face, you can activate it from the hand.
Strategy:
When playing this deck, you want to be playing more defensively and as possible. Time Thief Winder and Regulator are your best starting plays. And when you are stuff cards in Redoer or even Doublebarrel, you particularly want to stuff them up with spells and traps. That is where Time Thief Flyback comes in and Time Thief Startup comes up while in the grave. I generally made this deck where you can go 1st or 2nd, it won't matter much. So that is why I run stuff like Evenly Matched as a main deck card. Ideally, when going 1st you want to get out Time Thief Redoer and then get out Perpetua. When going 2nd, I would recommend getting out Doublebarrel or a different XYZ/Link depending on the situation.
Either way, I had a lot of fun playing this deck and I hope you guys get to try it out!

deck_excerpt: Space Dragons strong and will beat all.
deck_description:
Ritual Monsters are pretty interchangeable but the ones in the profile are the most valid.
  • Draconids- The staple for the archetype. With it being able to attack all special summoned monsters and it's 4K attack it can get over most monsters. And being able to get rid of max 2 monsters on the field from a quick effect and not being effected by monster effects is a bonus.
  • Quadrantids- The red headed stepchild of the group. Although not being able to pop cards as a quick effect, this card instead destroys all spell and trap cards. Although this effect is only a guarantee if you use two monsters with level equal to 2. Still it being unaffected by spells and traps and still having 4K attack is a plus. It's a good spell and trap counter if the opponent has a lot of spells.
  • Demise- Good for whipping boards and protecting monsters. With the only monster that will really stay on your field for the whole turn being ritual monsters, Demise's effect of protecting Ritual monsters from being destroyed by battle is great protection and a good support to have on the field
  • Amorphactor Pain- A good effect negator for extra deck monsters. This card negates the effect of fusions, synchros, and xyz monsters. A bonus effect the card has is the turn the monster is summoned, your opponents next main phase 1 is skipped. Although it could be beat out by a link monster with a high enough attack
Best set ups with ritual monsters:
  • Draconids and Quadrantids- Having the two boss monsters of the archetype on the field is always a good sign. With them both having 4K attack along with being immune to monster effects and spells and traps, it is a great board set up.
  • Demise and Draconids- Demise can destroy all cards on the field at the cost of 2K life points. Draconids is unaffected by monster effects so if you could get this set up going second you could leave your opponent with 1K life points left.
  • Amorphactor Pain and Draconids- With Amorphactor negating the effects of extra deck monsters and Draconids being able to attack all special summoned monsters, it helps Draconids get over any effects that could change their attack or negates destruction by battle.

deck_excerpt: Red-eyes and a couple of spellcasters.. Ready for 2021..
deck_description: Thoughts to consider below from a long time red eyes player...  Spam gearfried and black metal dragon combo.  Use one for one to help bring out a lvl 1.  Black Stone for summoning or Effect Veiler / rider of the storm winds for synchro.  Also World Legacy Guardagon for revival of a lvl 1 into a synchro or into Relinquished Anima / Linkuriboh if you're in trouble.  Use The King of D to play your Dragon Revival Rhapsody.  You also have the option to go for effect veiler with One for One, if you need a spellcaster for your Dragon Revival Rhapsody whenever The King of D isn't present.  Return of the Dragon Lords is your main protection from the GY.  Rider of the Storm Winds provides some.  Number 11 Big Eye will also get you out of trouble.  Successor soul too. This will help you dispose of an enemy monster.  When activating Dragon shrine, send Keeper of the Shrine as your second monster to the GY. You want him there as quickly as possible for safety and further plays. Noctovision is also your friend, especially to gain a second monster for your xyz.  Spam burn damage and fusion ASAP. Predaplant will be your friend here too if needed.  You dont need 3 Fusion or 3 Insight.  3 Red eyes will also brick too often so I stick with 2. I prefer 2 flare rather than 1 as you can often use his burn damage.  You also need to be wary of lack of draw power hence why I have 2 allure.  Still toying with Cards of the Red Stone and Reasoning.

deck_excerpt: Legacy of the Duelist Basic Casual Salamangreat
deck_description: Just my first attempt at a Salamangreat deck in Legacy of the Duelist. The deck is still missing some things and i'm running not that many copies of some staples here, and i'm using banned cards mostly because i'm playing against AI right now, i don't think it'd take many edits to get it legal in any case if i wanted to.     The maindeck:  monsters:  2-3 copies of the staples as deckspace allowed, plus x2 copies of Lady Debug. If i was to remove a Gazelle to adhere to Limited legality i'd throw in a 3rd copy of one of the monsters at 2, probably Falco or Spinny. I don't run any monsters in the maindeck over level 4, so i have to rely on Link Summons, and my Fusions to do most of the heavy lifting in terms of ATK, Jack Jaguar is the best at 1800. The monsters are mostly just trying to be value-machines to get the actual threats out of the extra deck efficiently.  spells: I run a lot of illegal stuff currently to beat the ai and to account for what i have in my collection in LOTD. Pot of Greed is simply the best card draw available to use against the AI so i'm taking advantage of the ai not caring about me using banlisted cards. i'm also using a full playset of circles for more consistancy v.s. the ai. if i were playing against actual people i'd probably use a 1-of of pot of desires and an extra MST, and, since Circe is at-1 i'd probably replace those 2 cards by beefing up the traps a bit by adding another CotH, and throwing in a Infinite Impermanence.     Traps: 1 mirror force to use in tandem with the raigeki for removal in case i have a hard time sacking a link monster for the removal effect on Salamangreat Rage. Since i currently use two Talkers in my extra deck, i felt a 1-of of Recoded Alive was justifiable. I'd probably cut it the second i got something better than the Talkers (cough savage borrelsword dragon cough another heatleo or so cough)     Extra Deck:  Currently only have 1 heatleo (i really need at least 1 more....) running the Decode Talker and Encode Talker to mostly beef up my amount of Link-3s. Firewall Dragon and the xyz are placeholders to get through LOTD stuff since they're banned, would ideally replace them with a second heatleo and maybe Accesscode Talker to get more out of Recoded Alive or Savage Borrelsword Dragon if i could fit tuners in here. (so if i was to play this deck against people the banned cards would instead be like another heatleo and either of the above options, if I went for Savage Borrelsword over Accesscode I would try to make maindeck room for Ash Blossoms, obviously.)  I have no idea what i would put in a sidedeck currently, i'm casual/new.

deck_excerpt: Shaddoll+ Chaos space= Banish to "shaddoll" realm
deck_description: This is a silly attempt to make a Chaos Shaddoll deck. I hope you enjoy it.

Code Talkers are all about getting monsters on the board. They may not be all that scary on their own, but the more Talkers you get out the worse it becomes for your opponent! With monsters that special or link from hand, summoning multiple link 3's is an absolute breeze. The two most important cards in this deck, hands down are Microcoder and Cynet Codec. Micro Coder allows you to search any cynet spell or trap when linked from hand and codec allows you to search for a cyberse monster of the same attribute as the code talker you just summoned. These two cards allow you to start picking up momentum towards and end board. Below I'll put one of the most basic combos that ends on an un-targetable Accesscode Talker To start this combo you need to have two cards in your hand. Balancer Lord and Lady Debug
  1. Summon Balancer Lord and activate its effect to get another normal summon
  2. Summon Lady Debug, activate its effect to bring Microcoder to hand
  3. Link summon Lady Debug and Micro Coder from your hand to link summon Code Talker
  4. Activate Micro Coder's effect in grave to bring Cynet Codec to hand
  5. Activate Cynet Codec
  6. Link summon Transcode Talker with Balancer Lord and Code Talker
  7. Activate Cynet Codec and bring Code Generator to hand
  8. Activate Transcode's effect to special summon Code Talker from grave to the zone he points to
  9. Link Code Generator from hand with Code Talker to summon Encode Talker
  10. Activate Cynet codec, search Lady Debug
  11. Activate Code Generator in grave to send Dotscaper to grave
  12. Activate Dotscaper's ability and special summon it from the grave
  13. Link Dotscaper and Encode to summon Accesscode Talker
  14. Activate Accesscode talker and target Encode, boosting its attack points by 3000
You can choose to stop on Encode to have two un-targetable monsters with Encode protecting Transcode and Transcode able to bring Encode back if it's destroyed. Other than that there are many more ways to go about this deck. All of the "Code" main deck monsters have abilities when linked from the field so you can make some spicy mix-ups with that. Other cards you really don't wanna sleep on are Prohibit Snake, a hand trap that bounces, Cynet Storm, a field spell that boosts your monsters and makes link summons unable to be negated, and Cynet Conflict, a searchable counter trap that negates effects if you have a Code Talker on the field as well as banishing the card and preventing your opponent from activating cards of the same name until the end of the next turn! This is by no means the best version of this deck, but I hope you have as much fun as I did!

deck_name: One With Nothing - BLVO Trinity Format
deck_description: One with Nothing is the abbreviated name for Danger! Dark World Plunder Patroll Golden Castle of Stromberg. Basically, this is a greedy midrange discard.dek that can do a little bit of everything depending on your hand, it has lots of niche interactions that let you more or less pop off. This deck doesn't care about the contents of your hand, deck or anything else, and can simply ram it's resources in to the opponent until it loses  Some interactions of note: Mirage of Nightmare is the best and worst card in the deck, you can use it to trigger discard effects, but really the deck wants it to draw in to handtraps and Plunder ammunition, The issue is that you can get stuck in a discard loop where you have no hand on your turn. I've included a high density of cards that allow you to remove your own mirage and keep the cards it draws, including all the quick-play backrow removal, Set Rotation, Forbidden Droplets, and even Hop Ear Squadron to go in to Vulcan the Divine. You can also do all these same things to keep Golden Castle of Stromberg from milling your deck, if you have a line in mind that you need to search for  Danger! Zone: usually, you want to use this when you have a Danger in your hand already. it is almost always a +1 or 2. It's actually totally valid to run 3 of this card, but points are fairly tight here and the third Whitebeard is usually better. If you don't have a Danger in hand, you can empty out your hand to fish for a hit with it, if you miss, you didn't really lose anything because it was dead regardless  Plunder Patroll: This archetype has to many wacky interactions for me to tell you, you really just have to play the deck long enough to learn them, but my main tips are: watch out for Xeno-Locks on Whitebeard and Goldenhair; All Plunder Patroll discards are costs so they don't trigger Dark Worlds, but this can be mitigated with Mothman and Ojama Pink; Getting 2 Shipyarrd in rotation enables the top end of what the archetype can do.

deck_excerpt: A near perfected Skull servant deck with Shiranui support
deck_description:
Main objective Summon "King of skull servants". To do that easily we need to get wightprince in the GY and almost no cards in the banished zone. Win condition Get your opponents Life points equal to zero. Why these cards? In this deck there is about 14 guarenteed ways to get wightprince into the grave. Now keep in mind if you put wight baking (new card) in the grave from your deck you either get a +1 or stay neutral with card advantage. When Wight baking is sent to the GY, you draw any 2 cards with "skull servant" in their text and discard 1 card from your hand which will always be Wightprince. With Wight baking's effect any Wight cards count as skull servants, so you can pull them out of your deck. He is also really good hand trap protection when you have a King of skull servant on the field When using Wightprince's effect to summon King of skull servants servant you almost always want to banish 2 The Lady in Wight or 1 The Lady in Wight and 1 Wightprincess The Lady in Wight completely negates the effect of spell and trap for all level 3 or lower zombie type monsters except for herself. This adds an additional layer to keep King of Skull servants safe Wightmare can special summon a King of skull servant or The Lady in Wight to the field, he can also bring a Skull servant or Wightmare to the GY. You almost always want to special summon either King of skull servant or The Lady in Wight to the field with this card's effect Wightprincess act as a handtrap and when summoned can send Wightprince to the grave, keep in mind her handtrap effect can also be used on the field and when her effect gets used she boosts "King of skull servants" damage by 1000. The main 3 benefits from the shiranui support is the 2 trap cards and syncro summoning from the grave. Shiranui style shallow slash can be used to get rid of backrow or to shut down your opponent's combo in their first turn when they normal summon. Shiranui style samsara stops you from getting OTK'd by banishing 1 monster preferably with 0DEF and also let's you draw +1 card by recycling 2 0DEF banished monsters. For example syncro summoning from the grave with shiranui, or recycling wightprince and wightprincess into your deck. Powerful rebirth is useful to bring back the King of skull servants or Wightprincess which will send another Wightprince to the grave and her handtrap effect can be used again or bring back a Gozuki to send more cards to the grave. King of skull servants does have 1 weakness, destroyed by card effects. However his attack can theoretically reach 18k and he can come back to the field when destroyed by battle if there is a skull servant to banish in the GY. Having 1 star also let's him benefit from Wightprincess's effect. Archfiend Zombie skull does help to remove King of skull servants weakness Mezuki is used to counter King of skull servants weakness Gozuki can be used to send Wightprince, Wight baking or the occasional Mezuki to the graveyard. Can also be used to special summon King of skull servants or Wightpricess from your hand when destroyed. Samurai skull Similar to Gozuki's effect, but he can only send 1 monster upon summon to the GY which is why Gokuki's effect is better there. However the cost to summon a monster from the deck is nothing and is beter than Gozuki's effect. Needlebug nest is used to get monsters in the grave as quick as possible also give King of skull servants an ATK boost Performerpal Pop-up is an interesting card, you can ignore most of it's effect except the first 2 parts and the cost. Send up to 3 cards from your hand to the GY, draw that many cards, pay 1000LP for each card in your hand. LP doesn't matter all too much for an effect this great. If Weightprince, Mezuki and Wight baking was sent to the GY you end up with 7 "skull servant" cards in the GY, a mezuki and you draw +1 more from Wight baking and +3 more cards from Pop-up to start your combo. All that potentially from just 1 card. Allure of darkness is a good staple card it let's you draw 2 cards, but be aware of what monsters are in your hand, otherwise you risk banishing monsters you don't want to. Update 1.1

Your King of skull servants should at least be 7000ATK by now and you have a Wightprincess for a next turn combo. You | Turn 3 Draw, you get Shiranui solitare. Summon Wightprincess to the field, send Wightprince to the GY, send The Lady in wight and Skull servant to the GY. Banish Wightprince and 2 The Lady in wight, summon King of skull servants to the field from your Deck. Use Shiranui style samsara send Wightprincess and Wightprince to the deck draw 1 card. You get Wightmare. Use Wightmare to special summon The Lady in wight in defence position on the field. You now also have a Shiranui Solitare for next turn use and you can now attack your opponent with 2 King of skull servants that has 8000ATK+. Your King of skull servants should now also be immune to backrow. However to read your opponent's monster's effects and be aware of any funny effects. Your field would then look like this Monsters: Wightprincess | King of skull servants | King of skull servants | The Lady in wight Backrow: Shiranui style samsara Opponent | Turn 4 If your opponent somehow survives, again you do have protection from Shiranui style samsara, you can use its effect with Wightprincess to not be OTK'd that turn. If your opponent targets Shiranui style samsara you can always still use it's effect, because its effect doesn't stop even if it leaves the field. You | Turn 5 Draw, you get a Needlebug nest. Depending on your previous Needlebug nest, if you got lucky and got a Mezuki in the grave you can always bring King of skull servants back to the field. If not you can always summon another King of skull servants, however it will only have 5000ATK. You can summon Shiranui Solitare, play his effect, send Shiranui Solitare to the GY, special summon Shiranui spectral sword from the deck in DEF position. If she gets destroyed you can syncro summon from the GY, if Shiranui style samsara is still there you can benefit from recycling Shiranui Solitare and Shiranui spectral sword to the deck to draw 1 card. You can also use Shiranui style samsara to stay safe from being OTK'd again if it wasn't destroyed. This can continue on if your opponent keeps giving you the slip. Shiranui spectral sword can also use Gozuki and Samurai skull as syncro materials in the GY.

Combos:

All the regular combos apply, the difference here is you want to build a strong going first hand. Everybody goes on about how Madolche is a going second deck, but let's be honest, in the current format going second is almost always met with 2+ negates. One if you're lucky. PSY- Frame would probably run better with the engine style, keeping monsters out of the GY but I own Ash IRL and still think it's a staple. Solemn Judgement to be safe, is there anything that gets past it? Probably, but chances are you won't have any issues. Paying half your LP doesn't really do anything, again, current format, duels don't last too many turns. Negate as much as you can to set up the EASY OTK combo. I won't be posting any actual combo instructions, these can be found everywhere. The dimension shifter is experimental, but hear me out: Perfect going first board/hand- Teacher (GY disruption) Promenade and maybe a chalice (1/2x negate) Ash in hand (pushing it but I have gotten this hand quiet a few times) Indestructible Hoot from Jelly, straight chillin Sistart (protect the backline) And bangggg Shifter to end. How many deck engines rely on GY? MOST This sets you up for an easy win. Going second is far more tricky IMO. Madolche doesn't deal with negates too well. You can always swap out/add as you please. The best thing about this deck is the freedom of choice. Keep that Side Deck handy cause there are so many swaps that can be made depending on your situation.

deck_excerpt: Pop and revive your spellcasters while boosting the whole field and searching or drawing constantly. Atrribute whirlwind
deck_description: Charmers are well... underpowered. I know this is not a shock to anyone, but the old beatdown style with different attributes and splashable ATK or DEF spellcaster values make this an interesting mash up. The new Charmer spell from the SD "Spirit Charmers" really gives the consistency to run the other archetype cards like Awakening and Possessed Partnerships. Awakening is a card the more competitive builds I have seen shy away from or only use at 1 copy, but being able to just amass different attributes to beat down over most monsters and getting an extra draw most turns is actually pretty useful, since the other engines do the control and focus on the extra deck utility. An obvious consistency booster would be Nadir's Servant, but I do not own any copies of that or Fleurdalies yet. I wanted to run 1 of each attribute charmer to make Awakening as useful as possible and stick to Charmers being the central focus. Dogmatika is an obvious pairing since having spellcasters that have 1500 DEF to revive off of the Charmer cards while being sticky and getting a lot of searches in is huge. Invoked is a 1 card engine that can utilize the varying attributes so I felt it had to be combined with the Charmers as well and is just standalone good.  I have not experimented with Shaddoll or Magistus cards in here, but I feel this combination is about the most competitive that can be made without having access to the $70+ cards (and only 1 invocation). Last thing that people could consider is the Dragoon package since you get a good amount of extra draws and searches it will always have discard fodders and is inline with the control and pop theme of the deck, but that would make 2-3ish dead cards if drawn and this deck is all about having a use for everything you draw (so no handtraps). Half the deck is dedicated towards Charmers to be super consistent and a fun rogue deck that can be built up with more $ and transform into the linear InvokedShaddollDogmatika if you want to get into regionals and be the most competitive. Not many techs in here as I run large amounts of each package/archetype and like how it plays with keeping it cheap (The 3x Ecclesia and 1x Invocation are about $100 and most of the deck cost).     Main deck Charmer package:  1x of each Charmer - they are vanilla essentially but synchronize with all the archetype spell or traps and provide more Invoked access. The Lyna is the clear cut since there is already so many lights in the deck and Fairy Tail Luna is clearly better to normal, just can't be used with Charmers S/T outside of the draw from Awakening. I just wanted to run a copy of each personally  3x Spirit Charmers - a 2 for 2 that lets you set up anything you want from the Charmer package and provides huge consistency  3x Awakening of the Possessed - boosts your whole field with each attribute and gets an extra draw a lot of the time. Also adds card destruction protection for the Charmer monsters that people usually overlook  3x Possessed Partnerships - reborn a Dogmatika or Charmer then pop 1 if you have 2+ attributes and can be used to put Awakening or Unpossessed back on the field  1x Unpossessed - a free SS for a different attribute 1500 DEF mon when ANY monster is destroyed by ANY means. Also gives a +800 ATK to your Charmer attacks and battle destruction protection to them. Only 1 needed since it can be recycled and searched from Spirit  2x Fairy Tail - Luna - a pseudo light Charmer that can search on summon and is a main consistency card, 3 is optimal but I wanted to run a Lyna instead. Useful for bouncing an opponents monster face up unless they send another one to the GY  2x Witchcrafter Golem Aruru -  a good budget card as it came in the structure deck and provides a quick effect bounce on an opponents card if a spellcaster is targeted or attacked. Useful tech that could be run at 3 or cut in favor of something else. Also just a big body that can come out pretty easy     Main deck Dogmatika package:  3x Ecclesia - just a super good card that pairs well with the Possessed Partnerships, Invoked, and slow down your opponent  1x Ashiyan - the 2nd best 1500 DEF from the archetype that can give a boost and recycle a card on top of being a free body from a Titaniklad send  3x Punishment - a great disruption that can generate advantage or more pops and is searchable     Main Deck Invoked package:  3x Aleister - duh he runs the whole archetype and is a 1 card fusion that can be used every turn and searched from the field spell and by extent Terraforming or Metaverse  1x Invocation - the neccessary spell for the archetype, I only have 1 of but am fine with these numbers as it doesnt lead to boring fusion and pray for the best hands  3x Meltdown - search and guarantee the fusion summons     Main deck techs:  1x Terraforming - Get the invoked cards live or slap down the secret village  1x Metaverse - refer to that ^  1x Secret Village of the Spellcasters - likely lock your opponent out of blowout techs and draw power without fear of it blocking you since you will almost always have a spellcaster in hand even if your monsters get nuked  1x Callled By the Grave - stop any annoying shennanigans  2x Crackdown - use opponent monsters for link material 0r just hold them to prevent climbing and effects. 3 would not hurt anything if a charmer mon or golem was removed     Extra deck:  1x of each Charmer link -  link off opponent monsters or steal them from their GY  1x Abyss Dweller - prevent GY extenders and use almost any monster card in the deck to make  1x Selene Master of Magicians - Link climb to bring back a choice mon  1x Borrelsword Dragon - Big boi get bigger, condenses your field if need be too, can be sent to out Zeus  2x Titaniklad -  send for Dogmatika stuff and search. A third copy is almost never needed and I only have 2 so it works out well  1x N'tss - send for an extra pop, only have 1 but 2 or 3 could be useful depending on the matchup if you are willing to cut something else from the ED  2x Mechaba - great control card and easy to make in this deck, if 3 is needed your game is probably so long and grindy you are in a bad spot as is  1x Caliga - 1 attack and 1 monster effect can lock many decks down. very underrated but only accessable by a sent ED card or the Dharc (not relying on your opponents monsters)  1x Purg - keep swinging and piercing, could be cut but I like the option for a fusion that can attack all monsters  1x Raidjin - flip whatever nonesense your opponent has down and can be brought out with instant fusion. 1 is plenty since you don't always need it but is a great utility to have     Side:  1x Pankratops - obvious good go second card, can help comeback if you get nuked as well  1x Feather Duster - ^  1x Raigeki - ^  1x Monster Reborn - sometimes better than the possessed trap because it can bring back your ED mons, but wont get extra pops or draws usually. Is a spell instead of a trap too  1x Set Rotation - matchup specific, but can annoy the hell out of opponents by blocking starters or make them pop it  3x DRNM - imo the best going second card right now and always is good to allow you to set up a board  3x Night Beam - after experimenting with each removal, this is the best for going second I have found. Does nothing for going first and probably wont be too useful turn 3, but they cannot chain the target unlike cosmic or MST and it has no card cost like twin twisters.  1x Pot of Avarice - Recycle and draw for a grindy match  3x Summon Limit - keep the wombo combos under control if you go first     Thanks for the read on my first decklist post and give me your thoughts and feedback below! Keep in mind I am a newer player who does not have all the fancy expensive cards yet and my locals has a ton of variety so I did not make it specifically to be anti-meta or degenerate lock. I want to know if anyone has seen others have success with the Charmer cards as well and if you guys like keeping in the Lyna + Dharc and Golem and any other spice to consider. The side deck is the part most open to change in my opinion. Lastly, this does do well on DB also and some people just quit after seeing spirit into awakening + a charmer then using punishment on their turn so that's fun.

deck_name: A New Way to Play Prank Kids! Combos - NEW META 2021
deck_excerpt: Prank Kids are no longer tier 2 and I believe they are now a tier 1 contender in the metagame. Prank kids recently took 1st In the Remote duel Invitat
deck_description:
Prank-kids were always a solid tier 2 option for the metagame. This was because it was a little too reliant on the normal summon and it lost to ash blossom. What was worse was that it could just not play against well established boards. Prank Kids are no longer tier 2 and I believe they are now a tier 1 contender in the metagame. Prank kids recently took 1st In the Remote duel Invitational and were undefeated (8-0)!!   Before we get into the deck explanation, just a quick reminder that I explain all of this, show all the combos and talk about playing through nibiru ALL in my Youtube video. Subscribing to the channel would be a great way to support me and also notifies you every time I upload!!   Link to the Video - https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iBrDJIQRxg8   This deck is inspired off of the 1st place build. I think the reason for Prank Kids to not shine earlier was because people were not sure how to correctly play/use the deck. This happens to all new decks and experimentation is the key to finding the best possible way to utilize the deck. Pranks kids is just another example. Prank kids have evolved and there are some changes to how the deck is played.    Problems and how they are addressed -
    1. Losing to HandTraps - The “new and improved” Prank Kids plays an additional number of extenders so that it doesn't lose to handtraps, especially ash blossom.  Prank Kids from before used Poly, Prank-Kids Pandemonium, Instant Fusion and in some cases even called by the grave. The new kind of build uses all of those cards and also uses Parallel Exceed. Parallel exceed is a great card to chain block the ash and it can also be used to make an extra abyss dweller which is a game changer in some cases because graveyard decks are EVERYWHERE in this metagame. 
    2. Extra deck Ratios - Another difference from the old version is that now prank kids is not a combo focused deck, but a control deck. The new version does not play Prank-kids Plan or the Prank-kids Rip-Roarin-Roaster and only plays 1 copy of Prank-kids Battle butler and Prank-kids Bow-wow-bark. Battle butler is the deck’s main negation and Playing only 1 copy may seem absurd but it can easily be recycled off of Prank-kids Pranks, a card that can easily be searched off of Prank-kids Doodle-doodle-doo. The only Prank kids card we are running 3 of (in the extra deck) is Prank-kids Meow-meow-mu and this is because it is the deck’s main link monster (a link 1) and can also not be recycled since it has a graveyard that banishes itself from the GY. The deck also plays some more generic removal cards in the extra deck including the Knightmares - Phoenix and Unicorn and Accesscode talker as well. Accesscode is also a great OTK card. The extra deck also runs verte to speed up the engine. 
    3. Playing through well established boards - The deck also addresses the problem of fighting a well established board very well. In this build of mine I am playing 3 forbidden droplet, 2 Cosmic Cyclone, 3 Mystic mine, 1 terraforming (to search mine and can also search Prank-kids Place) and the 1 Set Rotation (can search mine or place). I hate to say this but Mystic Mine is actually a very good addition to Prank kids. It was also used in the 1st place deck. It is a lifesaver if you get hit with something like a nibiru and can save duels. It is a win condition on its own. Forbidden Droplet is another way to clear boards and it can also counter True King of All Calamities, the most dangerous card in the metagame in my opinion. It is essential to play droplet in this because gamma cannot be played in prank-kids and also because VFD = free win for the opponent if you don’t have the right countermeasures. Cosmic Cyclone is great to deal with backrow, counters Virtual World and is a great removal option.
 
  • Comboing - The deck can combo fairly easily and every single kid is a starter. Place, terraforming and set rotation are also starters since they all eventually search a kid. The deck (counting the searchers as well) has 17 starters! The combo only needs any kid to perform! The nibiru proof version of the combo can also be done if you draw the right hand (combos in my video). The deck can also do the nibiru proof combos very easily and consistently. I have 2 Nibiru proof combos in my video for you to check out.
  • Handtraps and control - The deck is playing Droll and Lock Bird and ash blossom as the handtrap choices. This deck cannot run gamma because it will brick and doesn't really work in Prank-kids unfortunately. Droll is an amazing counter to most decks mainly Drytron which is literally everywhere. Ash is just a staple and can counter anything. For the control part of the deck, we have the Mystic mines, droplet, the knightmares, and some others. After you control the board, you can easily just OTK the opponent with accesscode. It may seem like it is a less number of handtraps but it really isn’t because of just SOO much removal the deck runs. 
    Again, I explain all of this, show all the combos and talk about playing through nibiru ALL in my Youtube video. Subscribing to the channel would be a great way to support me and also notifies you every time I upload!! All make sure to answer today's poll question! Today’s question is: Why is your favorite card in the game right now?   Link to the Video - https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iBrDJIQRxg8   Thanks, and I’ll see you next time! :D

deck_name: Lyrilusc Tri-Brigade NEW META 2021 - Combos and Decklist
deck_excerpt: Lyrilusc paired with Tri-brigades are the new meta. Lyrilusc and Tri-brigade work really well together.
deck_description: Lyrilusc paired with Tri-brigades are the new meta. Lyrilusc and Tri-brigade work really well together. The Tri-brigade cards just generate SOOO much advantage - It is literally like link summoning by banishing the materials from the graveyard!! The Lyrilusc part of the deck can get the combos going and can also search and special summon Nervall - a very important combo piece. Lyrilusc (Using Tri-brigade) recently took 2nd in the 2021 Remote Duel Invitational as well!    Before we get into the deck explanation, just a quick reminder that I explain all of this, show all the combos and talk about playing through nibiru and getting rid of bricks ALL in my Youtube video. Subscribing to the channel would be a great way to support me and also notifies you every time I upload!!   Link to the Video - https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sqPOhP9N3Ks   The deck is really powerful - being able to make infinite negate boards (using [YGOCard]Mist Valley Apex Avian[/YGOCard]) and also has access to a powerful floodgate ([YGOCard]Barrier Statue of the Storm Winds[/YGOCard]), removal cards like [YGOCard]Divine Arsenal AA-Zeus - Sky Thunder[/YGOCard], [YGOCard]Alpha, the Master of Beasts[/YGOCard], [YGOCard]Tri-Brigade Shuraig the Ominous Omen[/YGOCard], [YGOCard]Ancient Warriors Oath - Double Dragon Lords[/YGOCard] and some others. The deck can also consistently play through Nibiru! On top of all of that, the deck also plays multiple handtraps/removal cards like D.d Crow (Counters basically any deck that utilizes the GY and is also a winged beast), Droll and Lock Bird (counters Drytron!), Alpha (as I mentioned earlier) and Forbidden Droplet (counters VFD). The deck is also BRICKLESS! You may think I am lying right now because drawing cards like [YGOCard]Mist Valley Thunderbird[/YGOCard], [YGOCard]Mist Valley Apex Avian[/YGOCard], and the barrier statue are bricks. This is true but [YGOCard]Tri-Brigade Ferrijit the Barren Blossom[/YGOCard] lets you draw a card and place a card in your hand to the bottom of the deck when she leaves the field and you make her in every single combo/scenario and she always leaves the field (not sure why you would keep her in the field but there are always exceptions). So if you draw an unwanted brick, Just put it in the bottom of the deck!! The deck can also combo fairly easily and can end on (easily) an infinite negate board and can also have more interruptions on top of that in the form of apollusa and Ancient Warriors Oath - Double Dragon Lords just in case the opponent has something like dark ruler or a kaiju to out Avain. The deck also has tons of removal (I listed earlier) and can OTK the opponent fairly easily. The deck can easily break boards and clear the way for big beaters to destroy the opponent (Mainly Accesscode and Tri-Brigade Shuraig the Ominous Omen). Overall, I think TrI-brigade is a solid metagame contender and can take on the top tier decks as well!    Again, I explain all of this, show all the combos and talk about playing through nibiru and getting rid of bricks ALL in my Youtube video. Also make sure to answer the poll question down below!! Today’s poll question is: Do you prefer effect veiler or Imperm and why?   Link to the Video - https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sqPOhP9N3Ks   Thanks, and I’ll see you next time! :D

deck_excerpt: My take on a new and better Amazoness build.
deck_description: Despite what people will think about War Rocks, I've found that its actually easier to splash then you'd think. Especially when we already have an archetype based on EARTH Warrior's, am I referencing Gouki? I could have, but no, I'm thinking of an archetype that's older, Amazoness.  Amazoness was already a powerful deck based around Amazoness Queen and then later Amazoness Empress. However, they also fell short to what they can give at the table as spamming the field was difficult. Even with cards like Amazoness Spy and Amazoness Baby Tiger, it was missing something.  That's where War Rocks come in, most of them are indeed outdated and they are considered the Internet Explorer archetype since they came a little too late for their time period. However, Amazoness benefited off this new archetype, how? Maybe Gactos? Well, with Gactos around it did made it easier for Amazoness to spam the board and make Rank 4 plays off Swords Woman and Gactos being that they are both Level 4, but what's interesting is not only Gactos, but Amazoness also got a beneficial replacement Field Spell out of War Rock Mountain compared to their older in-archetype Village Field Spell which was not enough of a Field Spell to even consider running it as Village did absolutely nothing, however Mountain not only searches Gactos, but also protects ALL of your Warriors, not just War Rock. Its also the best dummy spell you could give to your opponent through Set Rotation while giving yourself something like Mystic Mine since it'd do absolutely nothing for your opponent (unless they played War Rock)  This being said, is this enough to consider running a War Rock engine?  Well...yes? There's also one other card that is in my new Amazoness build, because if you haven't noticed, I'm also using an easily accessible War Rock Skyler. But why Skylar? Well, its true you're not going to use her effect too much as it kind of sucks (but I guess if you wanted to revive a Amazoness Queen or similar then you could) But the biggest thing about Skyler is not only that she is spammable by both Gactos and Mountain, but she's a Level 6. Guess who else is a Level 6 that is also easily spammable by Amazoness Princess, oh right, Amazoness Queen. So not only does War Rock provide extra searches, protection, and Rank 4 plays, but they also grant Rank 6 plays as well. Which is why Photon Strike Bounzer is in the Extra.  With all of this in mind, I've based my new Amazoness build around the War Rock engine, and also added a few techs here and there like Mystic Mine, Set Rotation, Fusion Recycling Plant, and etc. that allows Amazoness to be at their best possible to not only spam the field, but still be able to control the field through various effects. At the same time, this is the closest thing right now where Amazoness can actually have a presence with Rank 4's and 6's and have access to a larger Extra Deck pool. Because Amazoness really needed another powerful Level 4 and also be more consistent. So even though it wasn't a new in-archetype card that helped, I can say that Gactos, Mountain, and possibly Skyler was good enough to at least give Amazoness more playability.  Keep in mind, this is my first time here, and also first post, but also wanted to share what I had on my mind recently and hopefully you'll enjoy this deck profile as much as I've had recently.

deck_excerpt: An update on an Endymion/Mythical Beast deck I did last week. After using it for a minute (and watching more of Pend God's videos) I made a few adjust
deck_description: For the most part I'm still using the same standard Endymion/Mythical Beast combos, however I increased Cerberus from 1 to 2, since it is a free way to get Jackal King/Garuda in my hand, and he's also a nice target for Magicians' Souls going second so that I decrease my chances of drawing into him and bricking (sometimes, when I already have a scale that I can't readily pop), and also for Selene to bring back so I can banish one of my opponents monsters.  I used to have 2 of Purple Poison and 1 Black Fang Magician, as well as 1 Allure of Darkness for those darks, but they were just really bad to have if I wanted to combo off and go into a full board of negates, as I would usually want to save my normal summon for Blue Boy for the spellbook engine, and also it just seemed really dumb to pendulum summon them out to link into crowley if I didn't already have Jackal King/Mighty Master in hand, as I would just use the spellbook engine to draw into my negate cards then with no way to summon them out.  Instead, I put in 2 of Magician's Restage and 1 Foolish Burial. This has turned out to be a pretty solid way to rack up spell counters while also adding more monsters to my field for link materials and drawing more cards. Here are some examples (its entirely possible this is just common knowledge for Endymion players but I am also fairly new to playing Yugioh):  1: If I had practically no pendulum monsters/search cards in hand, but I had 1 Restage and Foolish Burial, I would use foolish burial to send a Magicians' Souls to the GY, then Restage to bring it back and then use Souls to pop Restage/ (sometimes Institution too depending on my spell counters) to then draw more cards. This is really my main use for Foolish Burial, but I will also sometimes use it to send Reflection or Cerberus to the GY as a target for Selene, depending on whether I go first or second, if I don't have Magicians' Souls in hand to do this. If I do have one of my starters, then again this is also a really good way for me to rack up a ton of counters to search/special summon.  2: If my starting hand had Spellbook of Knowledge and no blue boy or secrets, but I had either Magicians' Souls or Jester Confit--preferably Souls--as well as a Restage (or if I draw into Restage with Knowledge instead of like Servant/Reflection/Abductor/Spell power mastery to start my combo) then I would use restage to bring back it back (and then send less helpful spells to the GY to draw more if its Souls).  3: If I have Souls and Restage in hand, then I activate souls, then Link 1 into Artemis, then Restage to bring back Souls, pop Restage to Draw 1, and then Link 2 into Crowley to run my spellbook engine.  There's probably more combos, but these are just the main ones I tend to use. Again, with all of these examples, assuming the worst: I am unable to scale anything and therefore I am not racking up counters, but with all my draws I will almost always get a starter and enough spells to get its counters, but if I am to scale even just one thing, then I can just get counters for days.  Also, Restage is generally just a good target for my Mighty Master to destroy whenever I want to pop him from my high scale on turn 1. I normally target Citadel if I have it out, so that I can use Citadel's effect to avoid destruction, but then Mighty Master won't get his counter for additional protection (occasionally I will also target Mythical Institution if I feel like I don't need it).  For my extra deck, I replaced Abyss Dweller with Bagooska since Bagooska seems like a more general way to negate monster effects (although I did side Dweller for me to switch out with Bagooska depending on the match up).  I replaced Geonator Transverser with Apollousa. Transverser was really just in there as a potential out to Dragoon, but I almost never used it to do that. In fact, I pretty consistently have been able to out Dragoon with Accesscode, so it made more sense to free up a space for Apollousa to get more potential negates, although I usually will end my turn with Selene out and Reflection in my hand/the GY so that I can bounce back a potentially bad extra deck summon/normal summon (and then I'll also keep an extra space for me to use Garuda to bounce back another similar summon if I can't use it to MST a facedown or an annoying continuous spell/trap. I still need to find a way to work Apollousa into my combos without removing my other negates.  Lastly I took out Thousand-Eyes Restrict, since Millennium-Eyes just felt like a better target for my Instant Fusion to its ability to chain onto a monsters effect and grab it for myself (especially the ones that "Can't be destroyed by card effects"), and I replaced it with Day-Breaker, for its ability to pop spells/traps, free up my scales, and also to get some more counters for my negates to use. I toyed around with using Saryuja instead to fix bad hands, but usually, by the time I have enough cards out to use his draw 4 effect, I would have already played most of my hand, so I would be removing 4 monsters from my field to draw one card, this being after I had already pendulum summoned/normal summoned.  When I'm siding out, I will usually take out 1 Cerberus, 1 Jester Confit, and 1 Restage. If I need to side out more than 3, I will then side out 1 Blue Boy and 1 Secrets, and I normally don't side out more than 5 cards, but also I might just not know how to side deck (please keep in mind that I have just been playing for a little more than a month at this point). Of course, it goes without saying that I'm interested in hearing any differing opinions you guys might have regarding side deck decisions or card ratios, since I am also posting this in part to get some feedback to improve my deckbuilding. Thanks!

deck_name: Consistent Pure Ancient Warriors OTK Deck
deck_excerpt: Kill and wipe out your opponents board in one turn with the bois straight outta three kingdoms...
deck_description: This deck strives to be a beatdown/OTK deck. The new support monster Lu Feng (and not A man's honor that card is garbage ) helps with the problems of Ancient Warriors a lot and gives the deck a little bit more consistency and power. The tech cards I decided to play: This deck is a pure second going deck, so I run three copies of Gnomaterial. Not only is this card a very good hand trap right now, it also fits perfectly with decks like Ancient Warriors which go blindly second. You want your opponent to build a board with some monsters, but an useless board which is easy to break and Gnomaterial makes sure it does that.  Next up I decided to run three copies of Foolish Burial Goods. When you usually look up for some Ancient Warriors deck profile, you will never see that card to show up. And I don't understand why. That card lets you dump Borrowing Arrows  or Metalfoes Fusion to the GY. Borrowing Arrows is a very important card because it searches out your best continous spell card in your deck and that is Three Visits. But if you already got the Three Visits on the field, just search out East-By-South-Winds so Double Dragon Lords doesn't have to do it and instead can search out a monster. I also decided to run Metalfoes Fusion because if you draw  Goods and Arrows that one card becomes useless in your hand so running that single copy of Metalfoes Fusion not only makes Goods more useful , but also boosts your consistency. Borrowing of Arrows and Metalfoes Fusion can both be send from the hand or field to the GY as a cost for your Ancient Warrior monster effects, so why would  you not play it? The reason why I decided to run Desires instead of Extravagence or Prosperity is because they cost a whole lotta money and it doesn't lock you out at drawing cards for the rest of the turn. If I run Extravagence in my deck, I can't use the second effect of Liu Xuan (tho you most likely use him as link material), the metalfoes fusion and the upstart goblin. NO SYNERGY. Also you don't really care about the resources you banished with desires, tho banishing your win conditions like East-By-South-Winds can suck. I also run a single copy of Cao De. I see a lot of decks cutting him out and I kinda see why because he is a win more card. But one of the main reason I run him is because of Lu Feng. He is much easier to summon now, because you actually have a way to pop one of your opponents cards ( not including mst or feather duster because they arent searchable..). Also I feel like he is the heart and spirit of the deck and probably my favorite monster and he is big beefy and chunky so run him at one copy. A lot of people cut out Lu Jing aswell, but in this deck, it is very easy to have at least one Ancient Warrior spell in your GY because of Goods. To control two Ancient Warriors with different Attributs is very easy, you just need to control him and a Guan Yun or a Lu Feng. Both easy and free special summons. His second effect is actually not as garbage as the one from Zhou Gong, as he can pop one of your opponents spell/trap card going +1. But Sun Mou has the best effect among all of them, because he searches a monster and bounces a monster your opponent controls. How to play this deck? One of the most common plays I do is I summon Guan Yun and pop one monster my opponent controls. Then I can normal summon Sun Mou and search out Lu Feng. After that I summon Lu Feng, pop and Sun Mou will bounce one card. Then I use Guan Yun and Sun Mou as link material for Double Dragon Lords and search out East-By-South-Winds. Then I bounce one card again and send East-By-South-Winds to the GY. Now my opponent cannot respond for the rest of the turn whatever I try to do and pop one card (non-targetting effect) as soon as I declare an attack. That also means they can't activate cards like mirror force or any of them annoying battle traps. With that being said, thanks for listening and I hope you enjoyed my deck list Edit: Refreshed the deck list a bit. Playing now a total of 6 handtraps and decided to play Effect Veiler instead of Ghost belle. If you can afford Infinite Impermance, go ahead and buy 3 of them thangs... Also cut a copy of Goods because playing three of them can be a bit bricky sometimes (hard once per turn). Also side deck has been added.
This is a rather trolly deck, you just try to melt your opponent with Lava Golem while surviving and stop your opponent from sacrificing.

deck_excerpt: A somewhat different approach to Dragon Links using Armed Dragon LV5, LV7 and LV10 from Blazing Vortex. I wanted to try something different and Armed
deck_description: Main Combo: 1 starter, 2 extenders  This is the main combo explanation, and for this One of the starters will be Starliege Seyfert, and the 2 extenders will be Noctovision Dragon and World Legacy Guardragon. The starting hand will consist of the 3 cards mentioned above, and 2 random cards. First, normal summon Seyfert, then use his effect to send himself to the graveyard to add Black Dragon Collaserpent. Then use the effect of Black Dragon to banish Seyfert and summon it. Link Black Dragon for Striker Dragon, chain noctovision's summon, and add White Dragon Wyverburster and Boot Sector Launch to the hand. Banish Black Dragon to Summon White Dragon and then link the 2 (White Dragon and Striker) into Dragunity Knight Romulus, and search Dragon Ravine. Everything up until this point should be standard dragon link plays. Use and activate Dragon Ravine and discard 1 random card to put Absorouter into the grave, adding a Rokket (search Rokket Tracer) monster to the hand. Then swap the field spells for Boot Sector Launch and summon Rokket Tracer from the hand. Then, link Rokket Tracer and noctovision into Crystron Halqifibrax. Draw 1 card from noctovision and summon Rokket Synchron From the deck as your tuner. Link the Romulus and Halqifibrax into either Apollousa or Unchained Abomination. (Going first make Apollousa, going second make Unchained) Link Rokket Synchron into Elpy and put him on the right-most zone Abomination or Apollousa points to. Activate Elpy's effect and summon Armed Dragon Thunder LV5 fom the deck. Activate Armed Dragon Thunder LV5 and discard a monster (Hopefully you have one in hand from your starting hand or Drew one off of Noctovision) Summon Armed Dragon LV7 from the deck and add Tempest from Armed Dragon LV5, because you can add a level 5 or higher wind dragon if it is sent to the grave to activate a dragon monster's effect. (Literally his own effect) Discard Tempest to activate LV7 and summon LV10 from the deck. Then using World Legacy Guardragon, revive a dragon from grave, and then link it into Pisty and then revive tracer from grave. Banish 2 dragons from grave to summon Tempest from grave, then banish Tempest,(Dont forget to add Crusadia Draco to hand when Tempest is banished) Pisty and Elpy, and summon Trishula from the extra deck. Activate Trishula and banish Dragondark to add Thunder Dragonhawk. Discard Dragonhawk to summon Dragondark from the banished. Summon Crocodragon (using Rokket Tracer and Thunder Dragondark) from the extra deck and draw 1 card. Then XYZ summon VFD (True King of all Calamities) using Trishula and Crocodragon. If you drew into Quick Launch, Monster Reborn or World Legacy Succession off of Crocodragon then you can revive tracer and pop Boot Sector Launch to summon a Rokket from the deck and then synchro summon Borreload Savage Dragon, and equip Halqifibrax from the graveyard for some negates. (Make sure to put your VFD and Savage into defense to counter Lighning Storm) Overall, I wanted to bring something new and interesting to the table, I hope you guys like it. Feedback is always appreciated.  Combo 2: 1 starter, 1 extender  Pretty much go through the exact same combo as shown above, except summon Omni Dragon Brotaur from Elpy instead. Then discard and target itself and add Chaos Dragon Levianeer, link Brotaur into Pisty. Summon Levianeer by banishing 3 dark monsters from the grave, (including Tracer) then summon Tracer back off of Pisty's effect. Then Banish Levianeer, and the 2 Guardragons to summon Trishula and banish Thunder Dragondark to add Thunder Dragonhawk. Discard Dragonhawk to summon Dragondark from the banished. Then do the same thing of synchro summoning crocodragon and hopefully draw into either Quick Launch or a revival spell for the additional Borreload Savage. Lastly, overlay into VFD for the icing on the cake and pass turn. (Make sure to put your VFD and Savage into defense to counter Lighning Storm)

deck_excerpt: An Odd-Eyes VFD Simorgh Combo-focused build (this is my first deck build)
deck_description: Intro This is my very first deck build, so please tell me if something is wrong or I can improve it. I was inspired by this Trif/Yacine video (https://youtu.be/PBz63A_Bx_4) and tried to make a different VFD build based on odd-eyes pendulum support. This is a very long combo and I want to tell you step by step how you do this combo. Of course, this combo has vulnerabilities: it is not Nibiru-proven and Droll & Lock maybe make you cry... But I still think it's a very good alternative to play using our lovely odd-eyes monsters. Edit1: I forgot the Elpy effect so in this first version I would not be able to summon Apex. I changed the Elpy target from Sloth to Persona. I still have one Extra-Deck negate if I need to and I can negate Elpy's effect and summon Apex on the End Phase. I think it's still a good combo. I will explore more variants later... Combo The main combo starts having Pendulum Call, Darkwurm, and Odd-Eyes Arc Pendulum Dragon in your hand. Let's go to the recipe: 1- You activate pend call, send darkwurm to GY and get Harmonizing and Nobledragon. 2- Special Summon darkwurm and get Gate Zero. 3- Normal Summon Nobledragon and link summon Halqi. 4- Special Summon the Winged-beast tuner which you prefer (I use Windmaster) 5- Link Summon Simorgh 6- Adjust your pendulum scales using Arc Pendulum and Gate Zero. 7- Pendulum Summon Nobledragon, Darkwurm and Harmonizing. 8- By harmonizing bring Stargazer Magician 9- Synchro Summon Meteorburst and activate it's effect summoning Gate Zero from the scale. 10- Activate Gate zero effect, target and destroy meteorburst. You will Special Summon Darkfire here. 11- Chain Link 1: Arc Pendulum Dragon | Chain Link 2: Gate Zero 12- Gate Zero comes back to the scale and you special summon Odd-Eyes Synchron by Arc's effect. 13- Now you just make two synchro 9 monsters using harmonizing and stargazer and using odd-eyes synchron and gate zero (by synchron's effect) 14- Go for VFD :) 15- Link Summon Elpy using the Darkfire to Elpy and bring Odd-Eyes Persona. 16- Negate Elpy's effect using Persona (to be able to summon Apex). 16- End Phase: Bring Apex to your field. That's it. Now you have the VFD, one omni negate, and one extra-deck monster negate.

deck_excerpt: WIP Use only as skeleton not don't play as is
deck_description: A deck for people who enjoy the Romance of the Three Kingdoms.
Write your deck strategy here...zgsg

Rawr stompy dinos. Dinosaur list based on turboing UCT, running some neat value in the extra deck.  1 Terraforming and 3 Lost World. I can't believe I used to cut this card, it might be dead sometimes, but in combination with other dinosaurs the card is nuts. 3 Token Collector, here for the combo - very bad as interaction since Linkross was banned, but I love the explosive potential of the deck. This card + Lost World + any dinosaur is the nuts. But generally the goal of the deck was just to turbo UCT, so most of the time all this is doing is getting to pill + dinos in the GY. Lost World also adds to Dinosaur's built in protection.  Miscellaneosaurus is really good, and a card you want to see rather than search, so it is a pretty obvious 3 of. Oviraptor searchs Tyranno and builds combos, but genterally your goal is to play under Nibiru, so who cares? They're one card starters, I'm running them. Animadorned Archosaur starts your combo so long as you have something to pop, and is an essential combo piece, so it's a 3 of even though you're usually searching it. 2 Pill so that you can usually pop something with it - that's the engine.  Pankratops is an obvious auto-include, I would run 3 of these in going second dinos if I could. Overtex Qoatlus is another spell negate, at its best the deck can still combo off turn 1 to a board full of negates, and this helps make that possible. 3 UCT because in this version you want to see it. I made sure to keep space to run 3 of these, I know you can often search him, but I want to come in under Nib as often as possible. Giant Rex helps make Rank 4 Xyz monsters, while Jurrace Aelo helps make Needlefibre. 3 of each of the babies and 3 searchers helps us to see dinosaur normal summons for Lost World. I also really like ending on an extra Pankratops early, and more Petiteranadon helps do that.  Ash and Nib because Ash and Nib are usually good going second.  Side deck is 3 Gamma and a Driver, for when you really need the power, 3 Dark Ruler No More and 3 Lightning Storm to break boards when you're going second, 2 Evenly Matched to go with the Lightning Storm and Pankratops for Spell + traps, and 3 Imperm because it is Generic and powerful.  No Extravagence because I don't like the card. It is powerful, and I have run it, and I will run it in the future, but I don't like it so this time I'm not running it. That technically makes the deck slightly less powerful, but I'm willing to give up card advantage for full playsets of the cards I want to run. If you were to run this list and have Extravagence you could just add them on top - the consistency you'd lose from having a 43 card deck is more than made up for when you do see those 3 cards.  Extra Deck is Halqifibrax, usually summoning Ash, sometimes using Ash to summon Aeolo. The Fire and Water Charmer are cards you can go into from there - The Water Charmer has a great target in Needlefibre, whereas the Fire Charmer can let you summon and opponent's Ash to go into Halqibifbrax, hopefully getting enough advantage to make a Link 4, usually Accesscode. Selene can be gone into when you make Needlefibre with Ash by making Aeolo into Relinquished Anima, or through other routes by making Archosaur into Anima. You could run Effect Veiler to make this even more efficient, but I wanted Imperm and Nib, and I wanted to run Anima anyways. Linkuriboh, Salamangreat Almiraj, and Secure Gardna help you get monsters into the GY for Pill while making few summons, a super nice emergency button. The rest is Rank 4s, because these ones are good.
