deck_excerpt: Locking your opponent out of special summoning using amphibians is T I G H T.
deck_description:
INTRODUCTION....

Have you ever wanted to infuriate your opponent using a bunch of frogs, some weird looking insects, a cat looking mannequin and a statue? Well if your answer was yes, then this deck is for you! If not, then......Why are you here? Jokes aside, it's time for some real talk.

Deck Description.....

Here I will describe the deck and talk about the purpose of every card in it, starting with..... The FROGS: First is "Ronintoadin" of course this friggin frog doesn't need an introduction, he banishs a frog from the gy to revive itself and it's not opt, which makes it great for extra deck summoning and other things. Second is "Swap frog" this froggy is great for setting up your gy and for providing extra deck material as well, because when it's summoned (normal or special) it allows you to send one aqua type monster from your deck to the gy (not opt) , it's second effect is to return one monster you control to the hand (usually itself) to allow you to normal summon a "Frog" monster in addition to your normal summon/set, it's third effect is to discard one water monster to special summon it. Third is "Dupe Frog" this smart boy allows you to search any frog monster from your deck when it's sent from the field to the gy, also while it's on the field your opponent cannot target other monsters for attacks except itself, which means that if you control 2 of  them you basically lock your opponent out of attacks. These were all the main deck frogs, now to the other main deck monsters. "Barrier statue of the torrent" this blue statue prevents both players from special summoning non-water monsters, this doesn't matter much to you since most of your monsters are water, also this monster is involved in the lock this deck was built around. Now for the Kaijus starting with.... "Gameciel, the sea turtle kaiju" turtle boi here doesn't need an introduction, all that matters is it's attribute (water) and that it's involved in the aforementioned lock. "Thunder king, the lightning strike kaiju" same as gameciel, the only reason it's in here is because "interrupted kaiju slumber" is here. And the last main deck monster is "Graydle slime jr." you basically use him to swarm the field, and to special summon "Dupe Frog" in case of an emergency. Now that the main deck monsters are done, let's get to the spells and traps. "Surface" basically a monster reborn to your frogs "Card destruction" To fill up the gy and getting to your combo pieces. "Foolish burial" to send "Graydle slime jr." to the gy, so you can use the one in your hand (if you have it). "Interrupted Kaiju slumber" nuke the field, summon Kaijus, and search Kaijus need I say more? "Fury of Kairyu-Shin" Search "torrential tribute" and protect your monsters. "Moray of greed" Draw power (can be replaced with "pot of avarice" since you might have monsters in the gy that you want in your deck.) Now on to the traps..... Let's start it off with the "Paleozoic" traps. "Paleozoic pikaia" Allows you to discard a "Paleozoic" card to draw 2 cards, good for consistency and triggering your "paleozoic" cards in the gy. "Paleozoic canadia" basically a book of moon in trap form, good for disruption. "Paleozoic olenoides" allows you to target and destroy a spell/trap card on the field, non-monster backrow removal is good to have. "Paleozoic dinomischus" allows you to discard a card then target and banish one card on the field. Now for the other traps.... "Storming mirror force" protects your monsters (since most of them have low attack and they most likely won't run over anything) and Allows you to bounce back your Kaijus. "Torrential tribute" destroying all monsters on the field can catch your opponent by surprise. Now that all of the main deck is over let's move in to the extra deck. "Paleozoic anomalocaris" and "Paleozoic opabinia" things to summon using your "Paleozoic" cards on the field and to search them. "Toadally awesome" Omni-negation, "Frog" searching, and recovery on death, there is a reason why this unholy abomination is the deck master. "Number 29: Mannequin cat" when a monster is special summoned to your opponent's field she allows you to special one monster from your hand, deck or gy with the same attribute as a monster your opponent controls (you summon "barrier statue of torrent") she also allows you to detach an xyz material to special summon one monster from your opponent's gy to their side of the field (only use this effect if your opponent has a water monster in their gy or if they have "Gameciel, the sea turtle kaiju" on their side of the field.) Needless to say, she is involved in the lock we talked about. "Mistar boy" and "Mermail abyssalacia" basically serve the same purpose, attack boost and recovery on death. "Marincess coral anemone" allows you to special summon a water monster with 1500 or lower attack from your gy "Salamangreat almiraj" you use it to send a normal summoned frog to the gy (usually "swap frog".) to special summon it, and it protects your monsters from effect destruction, so that's nice to have. "Paleozoic cambroraster" something to use your "Paleozoic" cards for and to search them. And that's all of deck, now to the strategies and combos...

Strategies & Combos....

Turn 1: Summon "Swap frog", send "Ronintoadin" to the gy, activate "Swap frog" return it the hand, Activate "Swap frog" discard a water monster to special summon it, send a "Frog" monster to the gy, activate "Ronintoadin" banish a "Frog" from the gy and special summon "Ronintoadin", XYZ summon "Toadally awesome", set traps if you have them, then end your turn. Turn 1 alt: Set, pass. The lock: Summon "Number 29: Mannequin cat", tribute an opponent's monster to summon "gameciel, the sea turtle kaiju", activate "Number 29: mannequin cat" target "gameciel" special summon "Barrier statue of the torrent". And that pretty much sums up everything you need to know.  

Notes & Afterthoughts

The side deck isn't really important as this deck is just for fun, and that's why the the side is filled with random water support. You can adjust it however you like. No one will probably read anything I wrote which makes me ask myself, why did I wasted almost 2 hours of life making this and submitting it? Which in turn depresses me. Well whatever I hope you enjoy the deck.

THE END.

deck_excerpt: Crusadia deck that can either go first or second and adjust itself better with the side deck
deck_description: Its the competitive Crusadia deck I use on my locals. Since they are pretty competitive and I have got some cool results, I decided to share my latest build on it.

Dytron budget Deck January 2021.

  • New Ritual-based combo deck from Genesis Impact that has a lot of recursion from the Graveyard, boasting a strong grind game as well as potent turn 1 boards that can win the game outright.

  • The level 1 Drytron cards tribute other Drytron cards or Ritual cards in hand/field, so this deck abuses Cyber Angel Benten's lack of a once per turn clause to gain a ton of resources and search a lot of power LIGHT Fairy cards, such as Herald of Orange Light and Vanity's Ruler.

  • Drytron Nova is an automatic 3-of inclusion in every competitive version of this deck, but also currently sits at around $40 each in NA. Novas are a massive boost in consistency, though the deck is honestly still playable without it, and is quite cheap otherwise. With even one copy of Nova, you should look to also include three copies of Drytron Fafnir (their Field Spell) which can search Nova as well.

  • The absence of Nova + Fafnir from the main leaves a lot of space to be filled. There are many ways you can go about this.

  • The sample list plays a small Pre-Prep engine with Herald of Perfection. It's very simple to play, especially if you're unfamiliar with the deck, and helps raise your overall ceiling - athough optimized competitive builds have generally moved away from Pre-Prep.

  • Another viable Ritual engine is the Megalith engine, which provides numerous options. These variants generally also suffer from consistency issues, made worse by the lack of Novas in the budget version. Less consistent access to Alpha means less consistent usage of extra Ritual monsters.

  • You could play cards that search Drytron monsters in an attempt to patch up consistency. Examples include Where Arf Thou, or normal summons that fetch Drytrons such as Cyber Dragon Core (getting Emergency) and Mathematician. Also viable is Neo-Spacian Aqua Dolphin, which is an interesting tech in Drytron that helps you beat handtraps like Droll & Lock Bird.

  • Finally, you can always just play more handtraps or generic power cards.

  • This deck is a relatively new deck, and is getting support in Lightning Overdrive, which might indicate that it's relatively safe from the next banlist. However, there's no telling what Konami will do, so don't take my word as gospel.

IMPORTANT: I did not make the deck. I coped it from reddit.

deck_excerpt: My go-to deck when I just want to have a good time. You like dragons? Got 'em. You like to bet your soul with cursed cards? It'll do that. You want to
deck_description: This deck is meant to shift and breathe, giving you a wide breadth of tools to adapt to your opponents on the fly like some sort of terrible Blue-Eyes swiss army knife or a particularly draconic hydra. As soon as they think they have you figured out, you can pivot on a dime and hit 'em with something completely different before they have time to react. The goal is to let you get creative; it draws consistently well but rarely plays the same way twice—that's the joy of it, in my opinion. Even when I lose with this deck I pretty much always feel good about the duel, and it's versatile enough to hold its own against just about everything I've thrown it at in MR4* casual play. I'm told it's fun to play against, too. It's a puzzle box for everyone on the field, not the sort of deck just out to curb stomp without mercy. And, as a bonus, it's super cheap.   So! Let's break this puppy down: The extra deck is minimal, because if you pull Orichalcos, it'll lock you out of summoning from it. As a result, getting an Azure-Eyes out early is helpful to keep grabbing Blue-Eyes from your graveyard, and once it's initially summoned you can revive it again after Orichalcos is played. Plus, its effect-immunity is triggered by any special summon of it, not just the initial synchro, which can be handy if you find yourself backed into a corner. There aren't many link monsters released as of early 2020 that work well with this deck, but Defender and Decode Talker are nice to have around if you've got the materials to keep making more Azure-Eyes or want the attack bump, and Decode Talker can be handy to tribute opponent's monsters who are causing you trouble. This deck basically has three kinds of monsters: Blue-Eyes, things that can get you Blue-Eyes, and ritual summons that will just absolutely ruin your opponent's day. You've got lots of options both for searching your deck for Blue-Eyes, and retrieving it from the graveyard. As a bonus, Melody of Awakening Dragon also lets you snag BE Chaos MAX out of your deck if you want. The ritual summons are the powerhouse of this deck. If you're playing Master Rule 4, they dance right around the restrictions on summon location, and they come with some extremely solid effects to hamstring whatever nonsense your opponent thinks they're up to on the other side of the table. Pre-Prep can net you the materials for Lord of the Red in one shot, and any Blue-Eyes card is enough to pay the cost—then just rebound it from the graveyard again with whatever retrieval method is easiest at the moment, and chances are that in doing so you'll give yourself a chance to activate one of his effects right out of the gate. Chaos Form takes a little more work, but if you pull it and don't have a matching ritual, chances are high you've got the materials to either pull BE Chaos MAX from your deck or strip it to the GY, and from there just bounce it into your hand with a relevant effect. BEWD variants tend to be pretty chunky as a baseline, but if you can add extra ATK onto them they become scary fast. You won't want to bulk up your baseline normal-summon BEWDs, since those are the pistons in your engine, but the effect, synchro, and rituals are all fair game. BE Chaos MAX makes god cards look like chumps if you can get her out and boost her effectively, because card effects don't kill her and she does double piercing to defense-position monsters. Power of the Guardians is a reliable way to start stacking ATK, and if you can get Black Dragon Sword out mid- to late-game, she'll just walk right over your opponents for fun. If you're really lucky, you'll have gotten Orichalcos out before her; that'll boost her by another 500 just for giggles, and also protect the weakest card on your field. You see where this is going. BE Chaos MAX in attack position, boosted, is a nightmare to take on in a battle of sheer ATK and card effects don't touch her. Claw of Hermos into Black Dragon Sword is a great way to give an ATK/DEF boost to just about anything. It can make Maiden even more annoying of a wall, or like we've already touched on, skyrocket BE Chaos MAX's double piercing damage to outright rude proportions once you've gotten a few dragons into your GY. Obelisk is... just a fun guy. Look at his big ol' arms. Who wouldn't love him? Maiden is a great stall if you're having trouble getting something you need, since looking at her wrong will grab a Blue-Eyes from pretty much wherever you may have misplaced it. And you can bounce quite a few other cards in the deck off her with a targeted effect if you want to trigger that yourself, too. Both she and your other tuners are there to get BEWD wherever you need it at a given point in time, but can also help recall BE Chaos MAX if it gets offed, or another Blue-Eyes variant with useful effects for the given game state. You've also got a handful of cards to drop your tribute requirements for BEWD and Obelisk. If you don't want to run Obelisk, swap your two Kaiser Sea Horses out for Keeper of the Shrines for some more GY versatility. The rest of your deck is dedicated to spell cards, largely ones that help you shuffle around your various dragons to where you need them. Depending on your opponents, and what sorts of decks they're running, you'll want to swap these around a little bit. Most of your control over your opponents should be coming from your monster effects rather than your spells and traps, but this is a good place to cover any gaps you find in your deck (my default build will go down fast and hard to banishings, for instance, because my local crew hasn't been running much offensive banishment lately). Just watch out for adding too much and disrupting the overall balance, because this deck's ability to keep shifting its loadout on the fly is its main strength and if you bog it down you'll find yourself in trouble with no way to keep monsters on the field. The BEWD effect cards are also a good place to swap things in and out to balance as you need. Beyond that... enjoy!**   *I built this because I'm a hopeless nostalgic and thought it'd be fun to craft a BEWD deck for Master Rule 4, which could weasel its way around the lack of link monsters that sync well with the archetype. I've yet to take it into MR5 duels, so I can't speak to its efficacy against the less-restricted special summons. **afterimage claims no responsibility for soul forfeiture that may occur as a result of activating the Seal of Orichalcos; please barter your mortality responsibly.

deck_excerpt: Elemental Mistress Doriado / Charmer / Fairy Tail (Post-LIOV)
deck_description: The idea is to summon Elemental Mistress Doriado so that each copy of Awakening of the Possessed gives all monsters +1500 ATK each (1800 if a DARK card is in play). You then proceed to beatdown with a bunch of easily summonable Level 4 / Rank 4 / Link monsters that become much more threatening with the additional ATK.  Dark Doriado makes all non-LIGHT or DARK monsters gain an additional 1000 (1200 if a DARK card is in play).  Magical Abductor searches Dark Doriado or a copy of itself and opens up a Pendulum Summon option.  Link laddering is easy by using Artemis if you don't have a LIGHT monster, then Lyna, then Selene. Lyna can steal an opponent's LIGHT monster from GY to make it even easier to summon Selene. Trick Clown can go into Selene by itself if you use it to summon Artemis, revive it, then use those two to make Lyna, then steal a LIGHT monster.  Fairy Tail Rella can use Bamboo Swords or Wonder Wand to draw more. Awakening of the Possessed combos with Lyna, Selene, FP Lyna and Rella to draw 1. Pre-Prep searches Doriado and its Ritual Spell.  Selene can summon Jowgen the Spiritualist from your hand or GY on the opponent's turn to lock them out of Special Summons. If you trigger Jowgen to destroy Special Summoned monsters while you control Awakening of the Possessed, your Familiar-Possessed monsters will survive destruction. This also goes for Time Wizard of Tomorrow.  Bujintei Tsukuyomi or Dugares the Timeless can be used as a draw extender and then goes into Drill Dozer Vespinato, which benefits from both Awakening of the Possessed and Dark Doriado's ATK gain.  The Dogmatika monsters can freely summon from hand if you turn 1 monster into Artemis or use Instant Fusion, which makes Link Summoning or playing Rank 4s easier.  Artemis and Fairy Tail Rella can be used to manipulate Cursed Bamboo Sword by attaching it and linking away or discarding it to attach another copy to Rella, then search Golden Bamboo Sword. Foolish Burial Goods also triggers it to search Broken or Golden Sword.  In a pinch Bagooska can be useful since it doesn't negate Doriado's effect (it doesn't activate) and your Link monster (Lyna or Selene) is unaffected by it.

deck_name: A Decent Phantom Knights Deck February 2021
deck_excerpt: A Decent Standard PK deck that is very fun
deck_description:
I felt like building a fairly standard PK deck with Just the normal toolbox the deck uses. Combos Are fairly non-linear but the end board is typically a dark rebellion with a RUM set to go into dark requiem for a pop and three negates, an apollousa for three, and a set fog blade.

Ratios and Stuff:

The Main deck:

Monsters:

3x Torn Scales, a great starter and extender for the deck, being able to dump any PK card as well as revive itself from the graveyard is very good in a deck like this 3x Silent Boots, an extender that also fetches a piece of backrow for your troubles 3x Tour Guide, the best starter in your deck, being able to fetch a graff from deck is really good 3x Kagemucha Knight, is a great extender that can chain block your tour guide so it can;t be ashed 2x Ragged Gloves, you mainly use this to dump either a fog blade or wing to get their graveyard effects to revive a card 2x Ancient Cloak, It can fetch you more cards for extension and that's about it 1x Stained Greaves, this is a fringe extender that can be decent for some combos 2x Graff, it floats into a BA, need i say more 1x Cir, You use this in the combo to revive Cherubini, but I tend to see that it bricks at more than one in this version 1x Scarm, You can use this during the end phase to search another tour guide for more plays the following turn 1x Tsuchinoko, this is just a really good extender 1x Jackalope, Another just good extender 1x Armageddon Knight, honestly not very good in this deck, but it can be used for some fringe combos 3x Ash, just a generically good hantrap, nothing really else to it 3x Belle, This is a meta call, both Drytron and VW rely on the grave, I typically prefer skull meister, but this one's level three so it won't be dead going first

Spells:

1x Foolish Burial, a good card to just be able to dump any monster from your deck 1x ROTA, It searches a lot of good cards 1x Called By the Grave, This helps you play around handtraps, I wish this would come back to three 1x Upstart Goblin, This is a placeholder card, you could play whatever over this, I just couldn't think of anything 1x Rank-Up-Magic Force, this lets you go into dark requiem during your opponent's turn, giving you a pop from rusty and three negates

Traps:

3x Fog Blade, this is a searchable negate that also can revive cards from the graveyard 1x Wing, this you use only for it's grave effect to revive a card 1x Shade, you use this as a free 4 for some fringe combos with AK

The Extra Deck:

2x Break Sword, This card is main use is to be popped by rusty to get two level 4s out to make dark rebellion, but it;s scrap dragon like effect is also good 1x Leviair, This can revive a banished card which comes in handy often 1x Dante, This card is a last resort if you've been interrupted or something and you need more stuff in the grave 1x Dark Rebellion, you use this to rank up into dark requiem 1x Raider's Knight, used for fringe going second arc rebellion combos 1x Dark Requiem, This is three monster negates 1x Arc Rebellion, This is a going second card used to OTK or go into zeus 1x Zeus, a plan B for most situations, but it's a very good plan B 1x Rusty, this dumps a PK and set's a fog blade, as well as popping break sword for the requiem combo 1x Cherubini, This is you main starter, it dumps a level three, that can be a graff, or a scales depending on the combo 1x Apollousa, It's more negates 1x I:P, this can let you go into knightmares on your opponent's turn 1x Unicorn, this can just spin away any card, great catch-all removal 1x phoenix, it's backrow removal

Some Neat Tech Choices:

The Dragoon Engine:

This deck struggles with the lack of backrow negates, Dragoon can fix this, but it tends to be bricky

The Utopia Engine:

The Utopia engine uses utopia double as well as utopia kaiser to let you go into Kali Yuga or VFD using the other RUM, it's just not very consistent and works better in it's own dedicated deck

The Dogmatika Engine:

I think that Dogmatika could suppliment the deck nicely, especially since requiem has the ability to revive an XYZ monster after a negate, such as number 38 for a backrow negate, however I find that I don't really know how to make the full value of this engine work, so if a better player can make it work, there are some cool interactions to be had there.

The Predaplant engine:

This could be another starter, it gives you 3 level threes for your plays by searching out instant fusion with cobra. I haven't found the space for it, but it seems like more copies of tour guide. Just a thought. This deck is really fun and I hope that it stays good for a very long time

deck_excerpt: The Chad HERO archetype destroys the beta meta decks
deck_description:
Hero's are one of my favorite archetypes because of variety of cool designs and how the archetype works. It still can keep up with the current meta due to all of the support it gets through out the year.
  • Droll & Lock Bird-This card is a counter to a lot of cards in the meta and a great option to have in any deck. Running three of this card helps the deck keep up with many decks in the meta.
  • Forbidden Droplets and Harpie's Feather Duster- Both cards can easily help clear boards. Most Hero monsters in the extra deck have high attack and can easily get over most monsters. Sunrise's effect of destroying a monster on the field when an attack is declared involving a Hero monster becomes more effective with Forbidden Droplets negating monster effects and cutting the attack in half. Harpie's Feather Duster is obviously one of the best ways to clear spells and traps.
  • Fusion Destiny-Good combo piece. If you haven't watched Teamsamuraixi's new Hero Deck profile he shows a combo from just playing Fusion Destiny.
    1. Use Fusion Destiny to bring out Dangerous by sending Malicious and Shadow Mist to the graveyard.
    2.  Banish the Malicious in your grave and special summon the Malicious from your deck.
    3. Link into Cross Crusader with Dangerous and Malicious then use its effect to bring back Dangerous to the field.
    4. Then use Cross Crusader's effect to tribute Dangerous to search Liquid Soldier
    5. Normal summon Liquid Soldier and bring back Shadow Mist
    6. Use Shadow Mist's effect to add mask change to your hand
    7. Link Dread Decimator with Liquid Soldier and Cross Crusader
    8. Use Mask change during your opponents turn to bring out Dark Law
    9. Using Shadow Mists effect you can search Honest Neos for extra protection for a 2900 Atk due to Dread Decimator's effect.
  • Evil Hero Engine-This engine is pretty expensive because of Malicious Bane so it's completely optional to run. I have it in the deck because of how much of an impact it has on the field. It can nuke the field and also can't be destroyed by card effects or battle.

Here's a fairly interesting control deck that utilizes the various support generic Water support to make a surprisingly strong  control deck that can shift into Beatdown for game's 2 and 3 if neccesary. The main point of the deck is to use your normal on the Marincess's, use them to load up the grave with the Marincess's you want in there. Afterwards, you use the Frog package, Scryp, etc, to climb up into one of the link-4's, which you use to activate your main card, a archetypal Imperm, from the hand. There's also the Bahamut plus the frogs to get an extra negate on board, plus some bodies. There's also the small Paleo package to strengthen the backrow and add in on the negates and interuption.

deck_excerpt: Pendulum Magician Deck Profile With Combo Tutorial
deck_description: The Yu-Gi-Oh! Trading Card Game Known as the Yu-Gi-Oh! Official Card Game (遊☆戯☆王オフィシャルカードゲーム, Yū-Gi-Ō Ofisharu Kādo Gēmu) in Asia, is a Japanese collectible card game developed and published by Konami. It is based on the fictional game of Duel Monsters created by manga artist Kazuki Takahashi, which is the main plot device during the majority of the manga franchise, Yu-Gi-Oh, and its various anime adaptations and spinoff series. "Magician" (魔ま術じゅつ師し, Majutsushi) is an archetype that consists of both Spellcaster monsters used by Yuya Sakaki and Continuous Spell Cards used by Yusho Sakaki in the Yu-Gi-Oh! ARC-V anime. They first debuted in Starter Deck 2014 with "Stargazer Magician" and "Timegazer Magician". The archetype is related to the "Odd-Eyes" and "Performapal" archetypes, both of which are also used by Yuya.  Link to use this deck :  https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=I0Spjk43WZE  Notes : 1.Pendulum call can be searcher with Duelist Alliance. 2.Supreme King Dragon Darkwurm with Odd-Eyes Revolution Dragon.  Requirements For Combo 1 : Pendulum Call + Supreme King Dragon Darkwurm + Oafdragon Magician or Dragonpit Magician.  Requirements For Combo 2 : Odd-Eyes Revolution Dragon + Duelist Alliance + Pendulum Monster for Pendulum Summon.  Requirements For Combo 3 : Chronograph Sorcerer or Pendulum Magician Monster + Pendulum Call + 1 Card for Cost + Pendulum Monster for Pendulum Summon.  Requirements For Combo 4 : Chronograph Sorcerer + Tuning Magician + 2 Pendulum Magician for Pendulum Summon.  Requirements For Combo 5 : Chronograph Sorcerer + Oafdragon Magician + Wisdom-Eye Magician + Lvl. 4 Magician Pendulum Magician.

Pk is a rank 3 XYZ archetype, which is known for 1. being a engine which was/is played in BA and 2. having really good support cards like tear scale's and bardiche. The deck was pretty bad on it's own at first, but with cards like psychic weeddealer uhm... I mean psychic wheeleder and psychic tracker as extender, the release of bardiche in legendary hero decks, Cherubini in DANE, the last support wave in PHRA and the release of tour guide of the banlist, the deck has now pretty good combo potential.  The playstyle of Pk is simple, firstly you try to get 2 level 3 monsters onto the board to summon cherubini, secondly you use cherubini to get graff or libic into the gy to get a cir out of the deck/hand or if you used tour guide allready to get one of them to the field and linked them of you can send any of your pk's to the gy and then you can go into bardiche and activate cir to get cherubini back onto the field. From here you have several options to come to the end board. The 1st turn endboard (if you didn't brick or got nibirued) is 1 bard which is equiped with a wizard buster dest. sw.,1 I:P (apolousa/knightmare uni.), 1 verte anaconda,  1 union carrier, 1 dragoon and 2 fog blades. And on you're second turn you're going to OTK youre opponent with accesscode and arc rebelion, if this didn't work you can use AA-ZEUS and I:P as a back up plan. The SPICE: 1 wizard buster dest. sw. is a great out against decks like drytron, it's basically a dweller for monster eff's.  The weak spots: This deck has obviously many weak spots, but I will only list the greatest. Artifact lancea, nibiru, forbidden droplets, dark ruler no more, Skull meister/ghost belle, d.barrier. Future support: This deck is always happy if level/rank 3 or really generic XYZ support (like AA-ZEUS or F0 utopic future dragon) is on the horizon. The next card that we could get in the TCG that we know of is F0 utopic future dragon which is an upgrade to F0 utopic future. If we get this here in the TCG the endboard could shift from I:P for apolousa to F0 dragon. And here is why: 1.It has protection against destruction effs.and battle, 2. You can negate a monster eff and steal the opponents monster if he controls it and 3. If you have dante as XYZ material and detach him you can recycle Cherubini.   And that's my Pk deck for the Feb. 2021 format. I'll update this deck as soon as new support is announced. Ps. when do we get F0 utopic future dragon in the TCG komoney?!!!

An aroma deck that utilizes/abuses synchro monsters. The deck is oriented around aroma gardening and blessed winds.
deck_description: This and any deck that uses the aroma engine highly relies on backrow not being disrupted. If your opponent has a fast way of getting rid of your backrow (by being destroyed or banished) then you can replace them, since the main deck plays multiple backrow cards except for 2 slecific aroma traps, they aren't as important as blessed winds. Otherwise your gonna set up and with a protected stardust dragon you don't really have to worry about anything, except for evenly matched. That card hard counters this deck, so if you really want, you could swap some cards for a predaplant anaconda-dragoon combo. But if your opponent negates your backrow continuously, you'r in trouble. Most likely your going to lose if you faced against a fast paced combo deck. But on the other hand, this deck holds some combos too. Combo 1: you need a tuner and any other monster (that's why i play mind control) to easely make halqifibrax. Combo 2: you will need 2 plant monsters and A LP gain when you summon aromaseraphy jasmine. You'll search angelica or rose girl, but if you have both you can search something else. Then you need an extra monster for the 3rd effect of aromaseraphy jasmine. You'll special lonefire blossom and keep in mind that specialing all 3 copies of lonefire is not a good decision since you want to draw it. Combo 3: if you have a dna surgery you can surprise your opponent by normalling rose tentacles or using fragrance storm on your opponent's monster. Combo 4: when your opponent declares an attack on an aromage monster you control, if you have humid winds: activate humid winds to search marjoram then you can special summon her and banish a card(s) in your opponent's GY. Apart from all of that, it's all control based and oriented around your backrow. The best aroma backrow is aroma gardening, it can stall you long enough to get you back in the game, after that the 2nd best is blessed winds. Your whole deck is made around those cards. If your opponsnt desen't manage to disrupt you hard enough, you'r gonna generate resources like crazy. Another reason why i play dna surgery is for your extra deck monsters to gain extra effects from your aroma monsters, and another bonus is that it can potentially mess your opponent's effects, so i recommend you flipping it before the main phase. Only con about dna surgery is that it doesen't change types in the GY, so you can't recycle your extra deck monsters. Best cards to foolish burial are rose girl and flower bot, but sometimes aromages especially laurel and angelica.

deck_excerpt: PK's with a pile of various generic Dark attribute support, like Dark Grepher and the Dangers!.
deck_description: So, here's what I refer to as a "Dark pile", AKA just a pile of fucking generic  Dark attribute support. The core of this deck is PK with a Danger! engine, to get fodder on the field easier for Bardiche, in order to set up a backrow of Pog Blade so you can pog the opponent's combo pieces. The Dangers! are fantastic for dumping PK's to grave and getting tons of bodies on field, and they also serve as a great source of draw power. There's also the duo of Dark Grepher and Armageddon Knight, which both help to fill up the grave to extend plays. As should be obvious by now, the graveyard is essential for this deck. I also included a small Levianeer package, so at the end of your plays, you can banish 3 unused Dark's to get out Levi and rip a card from the opponent's hand, making them start with 1 less card, as this is a going 1st control deck. In the extra, it's mainly a toolbox of various large monsters. There's Bardiche, which is your main large monster to summon as to set up a huge backrow. You also have the huge Xyz line-up, which is mainly there to be ranked up into VFD/Cali Yuga, but if you're unable to rank them up with Magic Force, you have the alternative option of poking in and going into Zeus instead. You also have the small Xyz Dragon package as to go into either Rebellion to finish off the game, or Requiem for negates, coupled with Pog Blade. This can make for an incredibly powerful deck if played right, but it sure as fuck isn't a meta contender for the time being, at least in my opinion. It's too fragile to cards like VFD and Vanity's to be able to go up against various meta decks. But, it's still incredibly fun and shows what PK is capable of doing in their long legacy. Update: Swapped around VFD and Cali for some better going first/second rank 8 options. Henry helped me with them; he's surprisingly chill on Discord.

deck_excerpt: Another format in which Salamangreats decided to burn their cease and desist letter.
deck_description: This is a weird format. The Meta is dominated by combo decks that end in floodgates, control decks that set for five only to xyz summon for six and every other deck is just Shaddoll. Players resort to religious punishment to obstruct their opponents and Invoked is still exactly where it has always been. Has anyone seen Dragon Link? At least one thing is for certain and that is that Salamangreat will find some way to adapt to whatever is currently meta and slightly change their deck to fit it's needs. If Fire monsters are good at one thing it's fighting fire with fire. If VW's emission scandal wasn't enough they've done did it again and brought floodgates back into the meta so the people at Salamangreat HQ (which is just a redecorated Sanctuary) quickly responded with, well, fighting fire with fire: Floodgates. The current Meta decks are incredibly divers in their types. Hence, Rivalry of the Warlords. VW has wyrm and psychic, Drytron has machines and fairies and Eldlich Zoo has zombies and beast-warriors and the occasional spellcaster casting Divine Smite with a Nat20 for way to many d8s. I also heard there's a new villain trying to take over the tri-state area. Well slap a fedora on your Rivalry and call it Agent R: Good news, you just won. Locking these decks into a mono type really messes with their board and if you're hit by a Nibiru because you're opponent is stuck in July 2020 you'll at least force him into rocks, rendering all of his monsters useless unless they are playing Adamancipator. You should be fine. If you're opponent has what is formally known as DINO DNA - You see, a few years back on a routine dig.. - or plays any other deck that has more attributes than it has types, Gozen Match is a fantastic floodgate. You can't access your Code Talkers under it but Salamangreat Rage's first effect can pop if whenever you feel the flood has done it's job and you can safely leave the comfort of the arc. Just don't get stranded on a mountain; I know someone who had that happen to him. Parallel Exceed, or friendly neighborhood...something..is back but he's not here to leave, he's here to stay! (think I kinda messed up the saying) He's not an extender for your turn 1 Borrelsword because you're not used to winning the dice roll, instead he enables a small r4nk toolbox with Abyss Dweller and Bagooska. Since you're not playing too many extenders (notice the complete absence of Will of the Salamangreat) you have enough space to comfortably run Called by the Grave and Upstart Goblin for a nice 39+1 card deck. Droll's dead this format, right? WeLl AcKcHuAlLy, I pReFeR lAdY dEbUg. If this is you then congratulations, you just graduated clown school. (It's an actual thing and it honestly sounds cool. I'm sure it made you a very confident person which explains your bravery to make such foolish statements.) Bufferlo can be chain blocked, it gives you draw power, dumps your Salamangreats, is a fire monster (which is very important for Gozen Match) and it's also not a bug but instead belongs to a near endangered species that could use some more representation. (No, I'm not talking about Chemicritter players) As always, Forbidden Droplet can be swapped for Dark Ruler No More and Accesscode Talker can trade places with Topologic Zeroboros. Almiraj is probably the most flexible extra deck slot but I've seen more hands with Parallel eXceed and a handtrap as my only NS than I have a seen the video of Trif Gaming getting banned from Konami. He did nothing wrong, man! Thanks for reading and please stop playing Mystic Mine. You know who you are.

deck_excerpt: RDA/Red Dragon Archfiend kickass deck with great consistency
deck_description: Here we have the RDAs -- an archetype many of us are already familiar with (maybe because we watched YGO 5Ds).  This deck recipe is one i have forged through trial and error, and the help of some other decks on this website. I believe this to be the most consistent form of the deck, being able to wack out Red Supernova on the first turn. This deck is pretty gamer in my honest and valued opinion. So, what's the strategy? Generally, you want a level 2 tuner and a level 4 non-tuner on the field to Synchro into Red rising dragon, and develop from there. The level 2 tuners in this deck are RED resonator, and CRIMSON resonator.  Red is decent, and it can aid in the recovery of life points if special summoned back from the grave via Red Rising Dragon, however, I prefer Crimson. Because, this way, If you have just summoned Red Rising Dragon and that crimson Resonator is the only other monster on the field, you can activate its effect to summon EITHER -- 2 more Red Resonators (LP bonus this way) or 1 Synkron Resonator and a Creation resonator (returns a resonator in the GY to your hand). If this succeeds, you have the perfect setup to go into Red Supernova Dragon - an incredibly powerful card, or (if the situation calls for it) King Calamity, by going into a RDA and then using your remaining two resonators to synchro in the the magnificent level 12 card.  I included 2 copies of Twin Twister just in case something like Zombie World is activated, preventing the summon of Red Rising Dragon. 3 copies of Resonator Command is a must -- it shouldn't be any lower than 3. Red Screen, as described in another, similar deck list (credit is where credit should be due) is simply put, a better version of Swords of Revealing Light. I included some draw power cards, because on the off chance you brick, it is imperative that you draw cards immediately, without waiting for the next Draw Phase.  That should be all, I tried keeping it as close to 40 cards without affecting the strategy. Thanks to the Rulers of Hell decklist for being the basis of my edited version. All criticisms welcome.

deck_name: Silent Magician the Silent Waifu with Hourglass Figure!
deck_excerpt: I special summoned Silent Magician the Silent Waifu!!!
deck_description:
The goal of this deck is to get your "Silent Magician, the Silent Waifu" out on the field as quickly as possible. How to play
  1. Foolish Burial Goods on Silent Burning and use it effect in GY to get your hand on Silent Mage.
  2. Always save Normal Summon for Spellbook Mage and Witch of Black Forest (link her out for Silent Mage, Nibiru or Aruru will help save your ass).
  3. Magicians' Soul can be use to put Mana to GY for more benefit. Do not use it effect to drop Dark Mage Girl to GY, Mana is a much better choice.
  4. Magicians' Soul can be use to dump Silent Burning while on the field.
  5. Magician's Soul to get Artemis then go for Silent Mage. Depend on your situation.
  6. Spellbook of Secret to get Spellbook Mage of Prophecy and use him to get Spellbook of Knowledge for more duro.
  7. Quintet Magician will wrecked the board. He can be summoned using Anaconda. He is definitely your trump card!
  8. Instant Fusion for Thousand-eyes Restricked to clear some annoying monster then link it to Relinquished Anima to clear more board (if it is point to monster) and use it as material to get your waifu.
  9. Palladium Oracle Mana make your Silent Mage LV8 immune to destruction effect. By summoning her when our waifu being target with effect your opponent will have a very bad-bad time.
  10. Apprentice Illusion Mage will help dump both her other incarnation (Mana or Dark Mage Girl) and Silent Burning to GY and help set up the board.
  11. Ash + any lv4 monster can be synchro to get either Foretune Lady Every or whatever level 7 synchro monster u want to play.
  12. Fortune Lady Every is surprisingly good. Go for her if you can. Swap Nibiru out for Effect Veiler will help.

deck_excerpt: A Lunalight OTK, with a Danger! engine for extra consistency. And nice tits.
deck_description: So here's a pretty simple OTK deck, as Lunalights center around fusing into large beatsticks and sending their monsters to the grave for additional effects. To load up the graveyard and get additional bodies on the field for Verte, I included a Danger! engine. They give strong draw power, along with dumping your Lunalights into the grave for their effects and getting bodies onto the field for link material for Verte. The Lunalights are mainly to be dumped into grave, except for the Pendulum, which youw ant to slap down into it's scale immediately. After you dump them in, you can go into Verte and use Verte to send the fusion spell, dodging it's hard once per turn and going into the larger fusions. Then you're able to swing in for a ton of damage and hopefully finish off there. The deck's incredibly consistent, can finish off the game in a single turn, and most importantly, it has furry girls with nice tits.

deck_description: Hello fellow degenerates.  Here is a version of Infernoble Phantom Knights that I've been labbing and having success with both online and in person play.  Any hand that can make Isolde, which is most hands this deck produces, can end on Savage plus VFD, a combo that's pretty solid at the moment versus most decks.  If you manage to find Torn Scale, who represents an additional two bodies via the other PKs, you summon Apollusa on six, ending alongside Savage, Herald, plus a level 9 synchro of your choice. Charles is the thematic choice, but there's a new generic level 9 synchro running around these days who's pretty good. Called, uh... Shenshen? Who completes the Macro lock combined with Herald so any card going to the graveyard from hand, deck, or field is banished instead.  Interrupted, I find I can still usually end on at least Herald plus Savage in most circumstances, which is not insignificant, especially with Drytron.  I'm open to criticisms and suggestions, of course, you all know where the comments are.

Plant (Shokubutsu) monsters were very overlooked and weak until support for the Type was released in the Crossroads of Chaos, Crimson Crisis and Raging Battle booster sets. A general strategy for Plant-Type Decks is to use cards like "Gigaplant", "Lonefire Blossom" and "Lord Poison" to fill the field with powerful monsters. They can go hand-in-hand with Insect-Types as well with cards like "Prickle Fairy". One of the strongest Plant-Type monsters is "Tytannial, Princess of Camellias" at 2800 ATK. It has the power to negate any card effects that target simply by sacrificing a Plant-Type monster (which in worst case scenario can even be herself). It can be easily Summoned by Tributing "Lonefire Blossom". In power and strategy, "Tytannial, Princess of Camellias" is followed by "Gigaplant", which has 2400 ATK and the power to Special Summon Plants from the Graveyard and hand. Other notable Plant-Type monsters include "Mystic Tomato", "Spore", "Dandylion", "Botanical Lion", "Glow-Up Bulb", "Nettles", "Cactus Fighter", "Meliae of the Trees" and "Number 50: Blackship of Corn"

Write your deck strategy here...ubjca

Swarm the board with Ojama and Melffys while getting 2 Kalantosa, Mystical Beast of the Forest on the board or in the graveyard. Then  summon a Joyous Melffys each turn to reuse your 2 Kalantosa to pop 2 cards each turn as a quick effect on your opponents turn to grind them out. If your opponent has a monster that can't be destroyed by card effects or targeted and can't be swung over using Ojama Emperor you can use Joyous Melffys effect to attack directly then go into Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder and use its effect to blow up the board. Other than that use Ultra Polymerization, Cattle Call, and Ojama Emperor to summon or resummon your fusion monsters and lock your opponent out of monster zones. Use Ojama Pajama or Ojama Country to search and discard or just discard Ojamagic early on to thin the deck and give yourself discard fodder while setting up for tri-wight. Unless you know your opponent can't use the tokens, never set Ojama duo, just get it into the grave asap with discard effects.

deck_name: Hot Red Dragon Archfiend King Calamity/Synchron Lockdown
deck_excerpt: This deck has a consistent way to summon Hot Red Dragon Archfiend King Calamity and completely shut down the opponet for their first turn :)
deck_description: If you like to annoy your opponets and completely decimate your enemies then this deck is for you! Long story short short: Junk Converter + Opponet with no hand traps = 90% win. This deck revolves around summoning Hot Red Dragon Archfiend King Calamity during your opponets turn which makes them unable to use any effects. In order to do that you will need to follow this simple one card combo: In order for this to work you will need to have junk converter in hand. He can be searched with reinforcement of the army or you can draw into him with the multiple draw cards which you have. The combo is: 1.Junk converter effect search for junk synchron. 2.Normal summon junk synchron and special summon converter. 3.Synchro into Junk speeder. 4.Use converter effect to ss junk synchron from gy. 5.Use speeder effect to special summon from deck "Satellite Synchron", "Cyberse Synchron" and "Steam synchron". 6. Synchro summon using Junk Synchron and Junk Speeder into Chaos Ruler.(You dont have to use the effect but it is good way to add cards like caligo and dopper.) 7.During opponets turn use steam effect to synchro summon using "Chaos Ruler", "Steam Synchron" and "Cyberse Synchron" into Hot Red Dragon Archfiend King Calamity. 8.His effect will trigger and so your opponet will not be able to do anything :) IMPORTANT This deck is not only limited to this combo even though it is its main purpose. You can try to go into as many synchro's as possible depending on your hand. You can also use any card that is on the field excpet steam synchron, cyberse synchron and chaos ruler since those are needed for Hot Red Dragon Archfiend King Calamity. P.S. This is the first deck that I have submitted so if you have any suggestions please tell me :)

deck_excerpt: Just a simple casual idea for @Ignister.
deck_description: This is my first attempt at building @Ignister.   Main Deck: Monsters: The usual @Ignister set of monsters for searching and setting up special summons, biggest difference is I field 1 Water Leviathan/1 A.I.'s Ritual for the boardwipe and have a ritual to have in the GY for Darkfluid, where other @Ignister decks run Gatchiri @Ignister, which i do not. Another difference is I field Lady Debug for extra search over Balancer Lord. Spells: Usual set of A.I./Ignister spells, I run 2 A.I.Land and a Terraforming over 3 A.I.Land to reduce opening hand flooding. Traps: a Mirror Force for extra removal, and an Impermanence for some extra negation (have another in the side deck if i feel like i need 2)   Extra Deck: Link: The Arrival and Darkfluid are the main boss monsters, with Accesscode as a backup. Dark Templar is used to Soul Charge out more Materials for links/synchros/xyz, while Fire Phoenix is a nice board presence card especially w/ TAI Strike. Wicckid and Splash Mage provide some cheaper link plays, providing either protection for other monsters or getting more stuff out of the GY. Synchro: Wind Pegasus is nice for some Spell/Trap nuking along with it's other effect, while Cyberse Quantum Dragon, like Wicckid provides protection for other monsters and also is a decent monster in general. XYZ: 2 Light Dragons. Light Dragon is nice. Sideboard: I have some stuff in my sideboard for getting more control cards to stay alive if it's an issue since my deck isn't as laser-focused on OTK as other @Ignister decks. (Lightning Storm, Harpie's FD, SoRL, another copy of Impermanence, Dark Ruler, etc.)

deck_excerpt: An Ancient Gear/ Trains deck that heavily utilises high level xyz and Ancient Gear fusions. The synergy between these archetypes is very good which ma
deck_description: This deck is as casual as they come. It's by no means competitive or meta, but it is interesting... This deck has 2 goals. Summoning high level xyz with the trains, the Flying Pegasus and the Anchor Drill and getting your Chaos Ancient Gear Giant out. Ancient Gears on their own are not that good in my opinion so a little support from an archetype that can frequently summon is nice.   Monsters Ancient Gear Golem: You don't really want to draw this card. You can't special summon it and tribute summoning this thing gets countered very easily which ends up with you losing 2 or three cards (if geartown is on the field only 2). It's why I put them at 1. I don't think you will even use more than 1 Golems in a duel. The longer the duel lasts the harder it becomes to win. Ancient Gear Gadjiltron Dragon: I can hear you thinking to yourself; "Why Gadjiltron Dragon? Ancient Gear Reactor Dragon is much better!!" True the card is better, but for what we are trying to do here Gadjiltron Dragon suits this deck better with it 8 star scaling. With this card you can get very easily into Seven Sins and banish your oponnent's monsters often locking them out of their effects in the process. This card is searchable with Urgent Schedule, Ancient Gear Wyvern and can be returned from the graveyard using Bullet Express Train. So only 2 as well. Ancient Gear Wyvern: This card is basically the Elemental Hero Stratos of this deck. It searches out any Ancient Gear cards in your deck. You can extend the combo searching for Ancient Gear Box first and then using the effect of Box you can add an Ancient Gear Frame or Infinitrack Anchordrill to your hand. You go plus 2 for no cost so run three at all times.  Ancient Gear Box: This the garnet in the deck so you really don't want to draw it. I run the card at one because it is recyclable so you can just use it from the graveyard again. Running at 2 could be possible too but I would not recommend it at three. The risk of drawing increases substantially. Ancient Gear Frame: When summoned you can discard one card in return for an Ancient Gear Fusion or Ancient Gear Golem. Handy card in a pinch but often you'll use Wyvern instead. We use 1 Ancient Gear Hunting Hound: A walking polymerization. When summoned it does 600 damage to your opponent but We use it for its ability to fusion summon any Ancient Gear monster. Often we fuse into Ancient Gear Howitzer to get an Ancient Gear Golem on the field. Definitely use 3. Ancient Gear Howitzer: In my opinion a very underrated card. Unaffected by card effects and it can inflict 1000 damage to your opponent... Every turn. Your opponent probably wants this card destroyed. But if for some reason he doesn’t and you don’t really care for the burn effect you can always destroy it yourself to get Ancient Gear Golem out to fusion summon a Chaos Ancient Gear Giant. If you have Ancient Gear Golem out in the field and you use Ancient Gear Fusion you can use material from the deck to complete the summon instead. So Howitzer is a powerful card that opens the path to an even better card. We run 1 or 2. Super Express Bullet Train: A rank 10 train card that is very easy to bring out. All you need, is to have only earth machine monsters on the field. Usually the plan is to bring out this card together with Heavy Freight Train Derricane and possible Flying Pegasus and Anchordrill to xyz summon your bossmonsters. Downside is that it can’t attack without sending 2 cards you control to the graveyard. This however poses no problem for us because we only use it as xyz fodder. A nice extra is that it lets you take back a card from the graveyard to your hand if Bullet train is in the graveyard. I run 2. I wouldn’t use three to prevent bricking. Infinitrack Anchordrill: Has enormous synergy with the Ancient Gear archetype. It is usable for Ancient Gear Box because it has 500ATK and it can summon another card from the hand. Besides that it can combine the stars for both cards making lets say Gadjiltron Dragon and Anchordrill fodder for the rank 12 xyz Seven Sins. Heavy Freight Train Derricane: Just like Bullet Express Train it is so easy to bring out. Use this card for xyz fodder too. Ideally we run 2. Flying Pegasus Railroad Stampede: Lets you summon a card from your graveyard in defense position but without its effect. Nice effect but we will use its secondary one more often. It lets us copy the level of another face up card to either Flying pegasus or the other way around. Best used with the trains or level 8 monsters. I use 3. Exodius: The Ultimate Forbidden Lord: We use this card as xyz fodder too and it lets you recycle the cards in your graveyard. One is enough. Machina Citadel: Same with Exodius: we use it as xyz fodder and sometimes you can use its effect to destroy your opponent's monsters. One is enough.   Spells (we don’t really use traps in this deck.) Foolish Burial goods: Use this to send Ancient Gear Catapult to pop Geartown. One is enough. Ancient Gear Catapult: We use Catapult to pop Geartown and summon Ancient Gear golem and Wyvern to get into Chaos Giant. Only way to really summon Golem aside from tributing and using Howitzer. Run three at all times, it is the foundation of the Ancient Gears. Geartown: Used in tandem with Catapult this can give you a Chaos Giant and more. Like Catapult, run three at all times. Ancient Gear Fusion: If used with Ancient Gear Golem you can search the deck for materials too. Chaos Giant can be out in one turn this way. I would run three. Terraforming: Speaks for itself really. Urgent Schedule: This card lets you summon 2 monsters from the deck. One lvl 4 or lower and one level 5 high or higher. This used to be quite an expensive card but is more affordable nowadays. Getting 2 free summons when your opponent controls more cards is very helpful for your xyz and fusion plays. I recommend running 3. Ancient Gear Fortress: I have mixed feelings about this card. On one hand it protects your Ancient Gears but on the other hand it is an extremely xenophobic card. When popped it allows you to summon an Ancient Gear monster from your hand or grave but for the rest of the turn you can summon ONLY Ancient Gears. So be careful with this one. I run 3 but you could run 1, 2, 3 or even none I don't really know with this one. Pot of Avarice: Very nice card to recycle your cards in the graveyard again and it gives you 2 extra cards in the hand as well. We use 1 or 2.   The extra deck Double Headed Anger Knuckle: This card is good for getting those level 10 cards on the field. We use only one. Ancient Gear Ballista: This card is a godsend for Ancient Gear players. It synergizes immensely with the trains and earth machine monsters in general. It only requires 2 earth machine monsters to summon it. Ballista can add one Geartown to your hand or any Ancient Gear Monster in the main deck. Usually what you want to do with this card is to add a Geartown to your hand, you play it and then activate Ballista’s secundary effect to reduce an opponent’s monster ATK/DEF to zero and send the Geartown to the graveyard as cost which in turn activates Geartown’s effect.  Chaos Ancient Gear Giant: The one card I’ve been talking about so much. With his 4500 atk and powerful effect it’s a force to be reckoned with. Unaffected by spell and trap cards and the option to attack every monster your opponent controls once. If that wasn’t good enough already it does piercing damage too. Run 1 or 2, it depends really. Ultimate Ancient Gear Golem: Sporting an attack of 4400 this card this card is quite the powerhouse too. Its effect isn’t as good as Chaos Giant but it can get an Ancient Gear Golem on the field when destroyed, giving you the chance to get another Chaos Giant. We run 1 or 2. Megaton Ancient Gear Golem: Essentially a weaker version of Chaos Ancient Gear Giant. When fusion summoned with more than one Ancient Gear Golem it can attack multiple times in your battle phase. When destroyed by card effect you can get your Ultimate Golem out and that way you could get an Chaos Ancient Gear Giant too. Superdreadnought Rail Cannon Juggernaut Liebe: A rank 11 xyz easily summoned using Number 81: Superdreadnought Rail Cannon Super Dora. Can attack up to the number of attached materials plus one. You can boost the attack of this card by 2000 by detaching one card which makes Liebe a powerful beatstick. 1 is more than enough. Number 81: Superdreadnought Rail Cannon Super Dora: Can detach one card to make another unaffected by card effects. When used on Chaos Giant it makes the card nearly invincible. Number 77 Seven Sins: Out of all the rank 12 cards this one is the easiest to summon. There are 3 ways to summon it and they all have their merits.. We can summon it the normal way by using 2 rank 12 monsters, this has the advantage that we can use its effect immediately and banish your opponent monsters. The only downside here is that seven sins has only 1 card to protect itself when targeted for battle or by card effects unless you don’t activate the effect. The second way involves xyz summuning Rank 8 Dingirsu Orcust of The Evening Star to your field. You then overlay Pain Gainer on it and then into Seven Sins. Last way to summon it is to xyz summon Ravenous Tarantula into Sevens Sins or first into Pain Gainer and then Seven Sins. We run only one, the resources needed for this card are substantial enough that you probably won’t get another one on the field. Number 84 Pain Gainer: Also 2 ways of summoning it but doing it the normal way  is not really possible in this deck. We mostly use Dingirsu or Ravenous Tarantula to summon it instead. Usually this card is just a stepping stone for Seven Sins or if you can summon Seven Sins the normal way and still have room for Pain Gainer it can be a good card on its own. We Also run one. Number 35 Ravenous Tarantula: If used a bit further down the duel this card will turn all your monsters into beatsticks on steroids. It adds the difference in life points as attack and defense to face up cards you control. This in combination with a Chaos Giant will completely destroy any monster. We mostly use the rank 10 trains or a Flying Pegasus to Xyz into it. If you decide to not go further the xyz chain and keep it as it is you can punish special summoning with it too. Every time your opponent special summons a monster they lose 600 lifepoints. And if that wasn’t enough you can detach one monster to destroy all monsters your opponent controls that have attack less or equal to this card. You could run 2 but I run one. Number 38: Hope Harbinger Dragon Titanic Galaxy: A very good  generic staple usable in a lot of decks. It has decent negate and forces cards to attack this one instead of another card your opponent wants to attack. When an xyz card is destroyed you can add half the attack of the destroyed card to another xyz you control. 1 is enough. Dingirsu The Orcust of The Evening Star: Really a good staple as well. I am actually inclined to use Dingirsu more then Harbinger in duels. You can use this card for Pain Gainer too. Aside from that it can protect cards from destruction by detaching materials. Run 1. Number 27: Dreadnought Dreadnoid: Can be used as material for Dora when you destroy a monster by battle. It has build in protection as well. I would run 1, it’s a good card but I don’t use it all that often. There is no side deck in this profile. I leave this to your imagination. Some examples of good cards I would use are Twin Twisters and Unending Nightmare. The rest is up to you.
Litho+Mechs

Been playing this for a bit, and realized through testing that it works better for me as a slower control deck instead of combo. So the primary strategy is to set up your twin loop while locking them out of the game with backrow and Gryphon, and using Abomination to pop cards on the field with Lil-la. This also allows you to use floodgates like order as one turn stuns because Abomination can pop them when you don't need them anymore. Excced lets you extend into I:P and set up Gryphon lockout, Unicorn spin, or Underworld Goddess. While Alpha is a card you can summon with either twin links on the field can act as spot removal and extend by being link material. It's not needed but its an interesting tech. If you don't want to play Gryphon and are looking for something more aggressive you can swap it out for an Accesscode. Don't know what the meta will look like post LIOV so hand trap ratios can vary, and always looking for ways to improve the deck so suggestions are welcome!

deck_excerpt: Windwitch supported armed dragons, looking for control going first and otk going second.
deck_description: I will be honest, this archtype doesnt feels finished yet and needs 1-2 more support cards to feel really fluid. However having fun and win games is not as big of a trouble as the first sentence made it sound. You summon big beatsticks, clear boards and throw hand traps as if you friend fell over and you just prepared a whole batch of snowballs meant for their face.  We split this deck in two paths you always want to do.  The Armed dragon path leading to a Level 10 Thunder / Lv10 thunder + White or vanilla for board clear,  And the Windwitch path which will  make you a protected crystallwing.  Thanks to the Windwitch combo not needing the normal summon, you just need to draw your bell or search it with wynn and start the combo. Afterwards you can do your armed dragon up rank protected under a crystallwing.  The key card here is Wynn, being able to either search the Armed dragon path starter or the windwitch starter gives your endboard quie the consitency, and if you already have both in hand, then she can search you a hand trap, where we also play a few wind ones.

deck_excerpt: If your family is expecting you to fight crime but Yu-Gi-Oh is your secret passion then look no further.
deck_description: Have you been watching questionable anime lately? Have your recent Gacha pulls been very lackluster? Do you believe Altergeist to be too strong of a tier 0 deck that would be unfair to play against so you wish to play a fairer control oriented deck? Whatever your reason to turn to S-Force I judge you by your life choices that led you here. But now that you have decided to fight the good fight in the name of justice and chase after I:P Masquerena all day and night (oh I see, so that's why you're here) we might as well have a look at a deck list.   You know a deck list is going to be good if whoever made the deck feels they need to explain and justify their choices beforehand. But alas, here we are: If you rather play Pot of Extravagance (because you inherited 500.000$ to afford those pots and all the extra ED monster it requires) you can easily cut out the Ghost Reaper targets. Since I'm instead playing Pot of Desires I chose to run 2 S-Force Showdown. Same with Orrafist, since he's not too bad. Well he's not good either but Ghost Ogre'ing a monster once is better than not ogre'ing at all.   "I'm sorry, I've spend the past week starring at Rappa Chiyomaru and have honestly no idea what this deck does": Well hello there, man of culture. If you haven't taken the time to go through this deck's line of plays by yourself - for completely understandable reasons - let me do you a favor and go through their 2 main combos. Rappa Chiyomaru + Gravitino: "I Normal Summon Aleister!" Sorry, force of habit. I meant Normal Summon S-Force Rappa Chiyomaru. You then banish Gravitino in hand for cost returning her to your hand to Special Summon S-Force Oka-San (apparently some people call her Pla-Tina). She will then Special Summon your banished Gravitino who in turn adds a S-Force Spell/Trap to hand. Add S-Force Showdown and Special Summon Chiyomaru from hand. Rappa Chiyomaru + Pla-Tina + any S-Force Monster: This combo too starts with Normal Summoning Chiyomaru. (I think I'm starting to get over my nightmares) This time you banish the remaining S-Force from hand for Chiyomaru's effect. This S-Force cannot be Pla-Tina since she cannot Special Summon herself with her effect. If you had Gravitino you could just do the above combo meaning realistically the S-Force you'd banish in this case are either a second copy of Chiyomaru or Orrafist. Now Chiyomaru will Special Summon Gravitino from deck who will again search you Showdown. Showdown will Special Summon your Pla-Tina in hand (yes, she only shows up at the very end of the combo, I'M SORRY!) who will Special Summon the S-Force monster you banished at the very beginning for Chiyomaru's effect. Tl;dr or the "still can't get my eyes off of Chiyomaru explanation": First combo ends in Chiyomaru, Pla-Tina and Gravitino. Second combo end in your banished S-Force, Pla-Tina and Gravitino.   "So that's it?": I hear ya (and Konami I hope you can hear them, too) and well, yup. That's it. A 2 to 2.5 card combo that results in 3 monsters on the board with no interruption. But what it does do is giving Mekk-Knights a run for their mechanics (and losing the race by miles). They affect your opponents monsters in the same column as your S-Force monsters. Most notably is Gravitino who makes it so that if your opponent's monster in the same column leaves the field it gets banished instead. So try placing your three monsters in the middle three zones to cover both EMZ to force their Link Monsters to get banished after link climbing. But the spice lies with the rest of your hand. There can be only one is one insane card. (What, you expect me to elaborate?) If you draw Specimen you can actually link 2 of your S-Forces away for I:P and then Special Summon Gravitino back in the same column as an opponents monster. I'd advise you to use Pla-Tina and Gravitino as link material since Chiyomaru's effect is a Quick Effect to summon another S-Force in a zone your opponent controls a monster to force a banish with Gravitino's effect if you happen to have another S-Force in hand to pay for her cost. (no I'm not keeping track of how many cards I'm hypothetically holding) Your Chiyomaru could then Special Summon Orrafist for an actual interruption. If all else fails, you have a good array of handtraps at your disposal with Dimension Shifter, Ash Blossom and Ghost Belle.   "Where's Isolde?": Another good point, well done. As nice as it feels to resolve Isolde, set up the aforementioned board with a bonus Apollousa I doubt you've played any actual Yu-Gi-Oh since your kindergarden days. The chances of your Isolde engine getting ashed at your Normal Summon is a high as it gets leaving y\ at the mercy of a bloodthirsty zombie lord and it's genetically modified human-animal hybrid pets and his intergalactic weapon of mass destruction. I wouldn't wanna be your Torn Scales. So where's the difference if they ash your Chyiomaru you may ask and you may not! Chyiomaru's a quick effect, your Gravitino is already banished so amy S-Force card will do to set up the same board during your opponents turn. So if you can't win anyways, might as we steal their turn. I swear we're on the side of justice!   Well, that should be about it. Now go fight crime and get your game on!

deck_description: Get Construct/Winda out asap, Dark Law for certain decks. I run him in main, but side deck him out for whatever I'm using.

this deck costs about 20 dollars and it's pretty good so i'd recommend it if you're on a budget. the springans archetype is also getting more support in lightning overdrive, and it'll make this deck even better. some flex spots in the extra would be cowboy, zoos, and phoenix. for the main deck, you could play 3 pathfinder, but it's a bit bricky, hand traps could be gamma, ash, nibiru, droplets, whatever. i'm broke though so veiler and ogre work, keep the hand traps at around 3-6 or you usually brick on them. you could change out retrograde, xyz import, or maybe flyback as well. swap pathfinder for springans booty when that comes out, the flex extra spots should be swapped for at least one springans merry maker when it comes out along with splind, and time thief adjuster will also probably be good for milling something like bezel ship after summoning it with regulator or and it can be to summon itself for a rank 4 off a winder search. the springans won't really do anything crazy unless you're going second, your opponent somehow doesn't have interruptions, and you open branga to pop some cards and search materials. anyways you're actual combos are mostly just regulator and maybe winder with a field spell and a springan. regulator can go into a board of 2 or so interruptions, including non-targeting, non-destroying removal, and a d.d. crow that attaches as material. unless they have ash. they gave springans terraforming rota foolish burial and aoe removal while also synergizing with a pretty powerful archetype that definitely needed something to go with it without playing 20 garnets, so it'll probably be good. sorry for being really lazy making this description, but i'm writing this at 4 am or so and not in a very good mood to use the shift key.

Fill in the rest of the extra deck with random cards. Here I will explain why I added some of the cards. Main Deck (40 cards) The 1x cards (Rollback, shadow, mask, goblin, cyber and Comic) The purpose of these cards is really to search them when you need them. For instance shadow toon is worthless on the first turn. 3x Toon harpie lady: These cards are very important. They are free special summons as long as Toon kingdom is on the field. Also If you play them whilst another toon monster is on the field you can destroy one of your opponent's spells/traps. This is useful to get rid of potential threats. 3x The Black Sone Of Legend: This card's purpose is to special summon Red-eyes then use Red-eyes to special another toon card from your hand. 3x Toon mermaid: Free special summon. 3x Toon Dark Magcian: The best toon card (in my opinion). The card's purpose is to set/special summon the 1x cards and to special summon Toon ancient gear golem and Toon Black Luster Soldier.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                          1x Toon Ancient Gear Golem: Great at dealing damage. 2x Toon Bookmark: I put 2 instead of 3 so there was room to add comic hand. Adds Toon Kingdom to your hand and serves as protection for Kingdom too., 3x Toon Terror: Great at negating spells/traps and destroying monsters. 2x Toon Briefcase: Stops your opponent from getting monsters on the field. Extra Deck (add cards so the total becomes 15) 1x Clear Wing Sychro Dragon: Powerful card that can be summoned once you side in Ash Blossom and/or Ghost ogre (use an lv3 tuner+ a lv4 toon). Side Deck (15 cards) 3x Ghost Ogre: If your opponent is taking control of the duel(s) using card effects side her in (can be used to synchro summon clear wing). She is a great replacement for Toon Terror; she can be activated from the hand. 2x Ash Blossom: If your opponent is doing the specific things listed on the card side her in (can be used to synchro summon clear wing). 3x Toon Buster Blader: Side him in if your opponent is using dragon cards. 1x Toon Rollback: side it in to deal damage as quickly as possible. Raigeki: Side it in if your opponent is getting large and powerful fields.

deck_excerpt: infinite negate turbo including a guide to the main combo and why I picked the cards I did!
deck_description: Main (40) Monsters (29) 1 Mist Vally Apex Avian (mist valley loop) 3 blackwing bora the spear (easy body) 3 blackwing kris the crack of dawn (easy body) 3 blackwing auster the south wind (combos with allure) 1 blackwng zephrios the elite (extender and vital to have) 3 blackwing gale the whirlwind (haha, repeatable attack cut go brrr) 2 blackwing pinaki the waxing moon (comeback move if necessary) 1 mist valley thunderbird (mist valley loop) 2 blackwing breeze the zephyr (add to hand = summon) 1 blackwing gust the gladius (conditonal summoning) 3 blackwing gust the backblast (great card to open with) 2 blackwing blizzard the far north (grave summoner) 1 blackwing hamaten the dust (you can play this at any number you want, I play one) 2 blackwing orochi the squall (easy monster to summon) 1 blackwing vayu emblem of honor (underrated extender)   Spells (11) 3 black whirlwind (gimmie more blackwings) 3 against the wind (looks bad on paper, great in practice) 3 allure of darkness (need I say more?) 1 rank up magic soul shave force (summoning infinity) 1 foolish burial (because why not?)   Extra (15) Synchro (6) 2 Blackwing full armor master (busted in some ways) 1 assault blackwing rikiri the rain shower (big numbers be like) 1 blackwing nuthong the starlight (another normal summon, black whirlwind) 1 assault blackwing soryo the rain storm (the synchro vayu summons) 1 formula synchron (explained later)   Xyz (4) 1 cyber dragon infinity (funny black card) 1 ice beast zerofyne (negates entire opponent’s field making sure you can go uninterrupted) 2 raidraptor force striyx (searcher)   Link (5) 1 smigbird bird of sovereignty (mist valley loop) 2 raidraptor wise strix (I don’t know if you even need to ask) 1 crystron halquibrax (after 2 years still terrorizing the meta) 1 union carrier (WAY too good for it’s own good) Combo guide:   Mist valley loop (with cyber dragon infinity and sometimes blackwing rikiri the rain shower)   A level 4 blackwing plus three other blackwings or two other blackings and black whirlwind, you can add rikiri the rain sparkling if you have three other blackwings (including a tuner) The requirements for this combo comes out quite often and is the main combo of the deck.   Let's say we have black whirlwind plus bora the spear, gale the whirlwind, and pinaki the waxing moon.   Link two of the blackwings for raidraptor wise strix, leave a level 4 blackwing there though! (if going for rikiri the rain shower then leave a tuner as well)   Use wise strix to summon blackwing zephios the elite.   Overlay zephrios and other level 4 blackwing for raidraptor force strix   Force strix detaches zephrios to add bora the spear to your hand   Wise strix sets shave force   Zephrios returns black whirlwind (if you have a blackwing tuner then summon the bora you added and return that to the hand) to hand and summons self   Summon bora the spear   (Side step, if you have the tuner then link it with bora to make crystron halq and summon vayu, whatever you do leave halq out)   Link force strix and wise strix to make smighbird   Link zephryos and bora (if side step was followed then vayu instead) to make union carrier   Union carrier attaches mist valley thunderbird to smighbird   Activate shave force to summon force strix and rank it up into cyber dragon infinity   Infinity takes union carrier as an overlay unit   (side step, if vayu is in graveyard by the previous side step then banish vayu and a level 4 to make shorya the rain storm)   End turn and smighbird summons mist valley apex avian.   (if opponent activates effect avian returns thunderbird to hand to negate and thunderbird summons itself)   (next steps are only if you did the side steps)   Halq banishes self on opponent’s turn to make formula   Formula quick tunes shorya to make rikiri the rain shower.   End, apex avian, smighbird equipped with thunderbird, cyber dragon infinity (if side steps completed then also rikiri the rain shower)   Overall a decently consistent deck that’s really fun and efficient against certain decks (drytron, virtual world, cyber dragon, phantom knight, danger!, and so on). I’ve had times where I would get the loop out and my opponent wouldn’t understand why I’m stopping them constantly, then once they read my field they just left, I’ve also had people who would leave as soon as I equipped thunderbird.   It has flaws like… um… kaijus? Yes kaijus are the main weakness of this deck, It also can die to super poly (to mudragon, not starving venom) or a player who’s smart enough to bait a negate and then attack your tunderbird. It also isn’t exactly what you would call nibruproof, just putting that out there.
